2. Product Background
2.1. Introduction to CTF
2.1.1. About the CTF competition
Capture the Flag (CTF) is a specialized competition format in the field of information security, where participants solve security challenges to collect special character strings called “flags”. The competition organizers design systems and applications containing vulnerabilities of varying difficulty levels, requiring contestants to analyze, exploit weaknesses, and obtain the flag – a distinctive character string used as proof of successfully solving the challenge.
CTF competitions serve many purposes: creating a competitive environment for individuals and teams, building a practical learning platform to accumulate real-world experience, enhancing information security capabilities, simulating real attack scenarios in a safe environment, and developing critical thinking and problem-solving skills. Many cybersecurity experts acknowledge that the mindset and methods of CTF nurture creativity, persistence, adaptability, and a continuous learning spirit – factors that have direct value in professional work.
2.1.2. Type of CTF Competitions
2.1.2.1. Jeopardy-style CTF
This format includes various challenges divided into multiple categories such as: Web Security, Forensics, Cryptography, and Binary Exploitation. Each topic will have challenges of different difficulty levels corresponding to different point values. During the competition, scores are continuously updated, and the team with the highest score at the end of the round wins; if two teams have equal scores, the time of flag submission is compared to determine the winning team. The challenge categories in this format include the following groups:
Binary Exploitation (Pwn)
In this group, contestants exploit vulnerabilities in already-compiled programs to take control, usually gaining shell access or arbitrary code execution to obtain the flag. Success in this field requires proficiency in tools such as gdb and specialized pwn toolkits.
Common vulnerabilities include:
●	Buffer Overflow: This is an abnormal phenomenon that occurs when software writes data into a buffer area beyond the capacity allocated to that memory region, leading to overwriting adjacent memory regions. For example, a program reads the user’s input string into a fixed buffer on the stack without checking the length; the attacker provides data longer than allowed, causing the data to overflow into the return address storage area of the function. The attacker controls the overwritten value, redirecting the execution flow to code controlled by themselves or to code already present in the program.
●	Use-After-Free: This is a vulnerability related to unsafe use of dynamic memory. After a memory region has been freed, the pointer pointing to that region is still used. For example, the attacker can cause the heap to reallocate the exact same memory region for data controlled by themselves, thereby overwriting important fields such as function pointers. When the program continues to use the old pointer, the execution flow is redirected to an address controlled by the attacker.
●	Format String Vulnerabilities: These occur when a program allows user-supplied data to be used directly as a format string in functions such as printf without controlling the content. The attacker can exploit special format specifiers (such as %n) to read or write data to arbitrary memory addresses, causing information leaks or taking control of the execution flow.
Advanced exploitation techniques based on these foundations include:
●	Shellcode Injection: The technique of injecting executable code into writable memory regions, then redirecting the execution flow to this code segment to create a shell or establish a network connection. For example, the attacker writes shellcode into the stack or heap, then overwrites the function’s return address so that the program jumps to the memory region containing the shellcode. When the shellcode is executed, the attacker can open a shell or perform system control actions.
●	Return-Oriented Programming (ROP): This is a popular technique used to exploit buffer overflow vulnerabilities, allowing the attacker to control the program’s execution flow by utilizing short code segments already present in the binary or library. For example, the attacker arranges in the stack a chain of addresses pointing to short code segments already present in the program or library, each ending with a ret instruction. When the function ends, the program sequentially executes these gadgets, thereby performing unwanted actions such as calling system functions or opening a shell.
Web Security Exploitation
This is a prevalent group of challenges, focusing on detecting and exploiting vulnerabilities in web applications. Contestants need to approach the problem with an attack mindset, thoroughly understanding the HTTP protocol, web architecture, HTML, JavaScript, PHP, and specialized tools. Common vulnerabilities include:
●	SQL Injection: This is a web security vulnerability that allows an attacker to interfere with the queries that the application sends to the database. This allows the attacker to view data that they would normally not be permitted to access. This data can include information of other users or any data the application has access rights to. Even, the attacker can edit or delete this data.
Example of SQL Injection extracted from CTF Handbook5: 
<?php
    $username = $_GET['username'];
    $result = mysql_query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE username='$username'");
?>
The attacker can enter the username string:
text
' OR 1=1 --
Then the condition OR 1=1 is always true, and -- is used to comment out the rest of the query. As a result, the database returns all records, the attacker can log in illegally or obtain the flag in the CTF.
●	OS Command Injection: This is a security vulnerability that allows an attacker to execute operating system commands on the server running the application. Command injection is a prevalent privilege escalation method in web applications and applications that interact with system commands. The consequence is usually that the attacker can take complete control of the application as well as all its data.
Example of OS Command Injection extracted from CTF Handbook5:
“import os
domain = user_input()
os.system('ping ' + domain)”
The attacker can enter: “; ls”. Then the command executed by the operating system is: “ping ; ls”
As a result, the semicolon will end the ping command, and the ls command is executed next. Then the attacker can list files, read the flag, or escalate privileges.
●	Cross-Site Scripting (XSS): Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a vulnerability that allows a user to inject malicious JavaScript into a web application, causing this code to be executed by other users’ browsers. Because JavaScript has strong access rights to the browser (DOM, cookies, sending requests), XSS can be exploited to steal cookies, impersonate users, or trick users into providing login information. XSS is usually divided into three main types:
o	Reflected XSS: Occurs when the payload is transmitted through a URL parameter and the server responds directly in the page content. Depending on the position where the malicious code is injected, its structure may need to be different. In addition, the malicious code can be modified to suit the attacker’s purpose. Whether it is extracting cookies and sending them to an external server, or simply modifying the page to distort it.
Example: “https://ctf101.org?data=<script>alert(1)</script>” . If the application directly inserts the data value into HTML without filtering, the browser will execute: <script>alert(1)</script>. 
o	Stored XSS: Stored XSS occurs when the payload is stored on the server, for example in comments, posts, or user profiles. This type of attack is more dangerous than Reflected XSS because it does not require a special URL while the browser is very difficult to detect and prevent, and the number of victims that can be affected is very large.
Example: Attacker posts a comment containing malicious script “<script>alert('XSS');</script>”. The backend application stores the original comment content into the database. When other users access the page (for example: the post page), the server will retrieve the comment from the database and display it in HTML: “<div class="comment"> <script>...</script></div>”. The browser will execute the JavaScript in the comment, allowing the attacker to access and retrieve the victim’s cookie and login token data.
o	DOM XSS: The DOM XSS vulnerability is an XSS vulnerability caused by the browser itself injecting malicious XSS code into the DOM. Although the server can effectively prevent XSS, client-side scripts can still accidentally retrieve the malicious code and insert it into the DOM, causing the vulnerability to be triggered. The error is not on the server but on the client-side JavaScript files that cause the problem.
Example: 
Client-side code: “<script>document.write(location.search);</script>”
The attacker sends the victim a URL like this:
https://vulnerable-site.com/?<script>alert(1)</script>
Then the client-side JavaScript retrieves the data from the URL (location.search) and writes it directly into document.write without checking, allowing the attacker to execute arbitrary JavaScript code in the user’s browser.
●	Directory Traversal: Directory Traversal attack vulnerability is a vulnerability in which the application receives input data from the user and uses it in the directory path. Any type of path controlled by the user’s input data that is not handled correctly or not protected in an isolated environment (sandbox) can be easily attacked by directory traversal. This vulnerability is very often used to leak sensitive data or extract application source code to find other vulnerabilities.
Example of Directory Traversal extracted from CTF Handbook5:
<?php
$page = $_GET['page'];
include("/var/www/html/" . $page);
?>
The application expects the user to enter “?page=index.php”, then it will load “/var/www/html/index.php”. The attacker will change the page value to: “?page=../../../../etc/passwd”. PHP will not check the page value, and the string “../../../../” will cause the operating system to go up to the parent directory, resulting in the system accessing the path “/etc/passwd”. As a result, the passwd file is read, and sensitive user account information is returned directly to the browser.
●	Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF): This is a web security vulnerability that allows an attacker to force the server-side application to send requests to unwanted addresses. The attacker can force the server to send requests to services that are only used internally within the organization’s infrastructure, such as internal services, databases, or administrative APIs that normally cannot be accessed directly from the outside. This can lead to leakage of sensitive data, such as authentication information or access tokens.
Example of Server-Side Request Forgery from Port Swigger6:
The app checks inventory, the server will send a request to the URL in stockApi and return the result to the user:
“stockApi=http://stock.weliketoshop.net:8080/product/stock/check”
The attacker will change the url to: “stockApi=http://localhost/admin”. As a result, the server will send a request to itself (localhost). And because the request comes from the internal server, authentication or access control steps will be skipped, and as a result the server will retrieve the content of the URL /admin and return it to the user and grant full access rights to the administration function.
Cryptography
Cryptography in CTF focuses on encryption and decryption problems, from classic cipher systems to modern algorithms currently used in practice. The contestant’s goal is to recover plaintext from ciphertext, find the secret key, or vice versa, based on analyzing the algorithm and errors in the way the cipher is used. Cryptography challenge types in CTF include:
●	Classical Ciphers: These are historical encryption methods such as Caesar, Vigenère, Substitution, Hill, Playfair. These cipher systems are usually based on substituting or permuting characters in the original text. Breaking classical cipher systems is usually based on frequency analysis of characters, guessing key length or trying all possible possibilities.
●	Hash Functions: Hashing functions are one-way functions used to convert any data (string, file…) into a fixed value, called hash or digest. This algorithm always produces output of fixed length, regardless of how large or small the original input is.
Example of Hash Functions:
The attacker can use a Rainbow table – a pre-computed table of original passwords → corresponding hashes. For example:
password   → 5f4dcc3b5aa765d61d8327deb882cf99
123456     → e10adc3949ba59abbe56e057f20f883e
admin      → 21232f297a57a5a743894a0e4a801fc3
qwerty     → d8578edf8458ce06fbc5bb76a58c5ca4
The attacker only needs to compare the hash in the database to reverse-engineer the password, thereby logging into the user account or obtaining the flag.
●	Stream Cipher and One-Time Pad Reuse: This is a challenge type that exploits the error of keystream reuse in Stream Ciphers. When the same keystream is used to encrypt multiple different plaintexts, the attacker can combine the ciphertexts to remove the keystream, thereby deducing the relationship or content of the plaintext.
Suppose a system uses a stream cipher and reuses the same keystream K to encrypt two different plaintexts: P1 = "HELLO123", P2 = "flag{test}". The encryption process: C1 = P1 ⊕ K, C2 = P2 ⊕ K. The attacker does not know K, but can obtain C1 and C2. Then the attacker calculates: C1 ⊕ C2 = (P1 ⊕ K) ⊕ (P2 ⊕ K) = P1 ⊕ P2. If the attacker guesses part of the plaintext, for example knowing that the flag usually starts with "flag{", then a known-plaintext attack can be performed: (P1 ⊕ P2)[0:5] ⊕ "flag{" → deduce "HELLO".
Digital Forensics
Digital Forensics in Capture The Flag (CTF) competitions focuses on collecting, analyzing, and recovering digital data to find hidden evidence or reconstruct events that occurred in the system. Challenges in this field usually simulate real investigation situations, in which contestants must analyze digital artifacts such as system files, memory, network traffic, logs or deleted data to trace user or attacker behavior.
●	File Forensics: Focuses on analyzing files to find hidden, concealed or altered data. Contestants must examine file structure, metadata, format signatures or embedded content in files such as images, audio, video, PDF or compressed files.
Example of File Forensics: When opening a file with a hex editor, the first bytes are seen: “FF D8 FF E0 00 10 4A 46 49 46 00”, in ASCII form, this string corresponds to: “ÿØÿà JFIF”. Looking up in the file signature database shows this is a JPEG/JFIF image file. The attacker can check on Linux with the command: “file file-a.jpg” and obtain the result “JPEG image data, JFIF standard 1.01, 1024x576, baseline”. Once the file format is identified, the attacker can use image processing tools to exploit metadata – which may contain hidden flag data.
●	Memory Forensics: This is a challenge type that requires analysis of a running system’s memory snapshot (memory dump). Through surveying data in RAM, contestants can find running processes, sensitive data, network connections or artifacts that do not exist on disk. Memory dumps are usually large in size but can be analyzed effectively using popular tools today: Volatility Framework.
A basic execution process will include the following steps: First, extract strings to find quick clues. Next, identify the operating system profile of the memory dump. The third step is to extract processes and search for suspicious processes (for example: powershell.exe, notepad.exe). After identifying the suspicious process, extract data from those processes and open it with the appropriate tool such as Word for .docx files or Notepad for .txt files. For example, notepad.exe dump: “python vol.py -f image.raw --profile=Win7SP0x64 memdump -p 2019 -D dump/”, the result is a .dmp file containing the entire RAM data of the process which may include: unsaved data, plaintext flag.
●	Network Forensics: Network Forensics is the process of analyzing network traffic to collect, investigate and reconstruct activities that have taken place on the system. Network forensics usually focuses on analyzing PCAP (Packet Capture) files, which are recordings of all packets transmitted over the network at a certain time. PCAP files allow analysts to observe each packet in detail, including protocol information, source/destination IP addresses, network ports and especially payload data – where sensitive information or flags are often contained in plaintext.
Example of exploiting Packet Capture in Network Forensics: Suppose an attacker has gained access to a machine in the internal network (for example via SSH). The attacker uses tcpdump to collect network traffic on the eth0 interface – a network interface on the Linux/Unix operating system, to monitor data transmitted over the network: “sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -w traffic.pcap”. During this process, the attacker detects unencrypted HTTP packets. Then, the traffic.pcap file is opened with Wireshark to analyze the payload of HTTP request/response packets in detail. Here, the attacker can obtain login information, session cookies or flags transmitted in plaintext.
●	Steganography: The technique of hiding information is a method of hiding information in various media, such as images, audio, text, or video. Hiding information is usually achieved by embedding secret data into existing data in a way that is difficult to detect. Steganography topics include:
○	Text steganography: Messages can be hidden by changing the size of spaces, or in text without diacritics.
○	Audio steganography: In audio files, information can be hidden by modifying inaudible frequency bands or adding to any area in the audio without affecting quality.
○	Video steganography: Information can be hidden in unimportant frames in the video.
○	Image steganography: Information can be hidden in the least significant bits of pixels. For example, changing the smallest RGB value of each pixel does not significantly change the image but still contains secret information.
Reverse Engineering
Reverse Engineering in CTF is a group of challenges that requires analyzing already-compiled programs (such as ELF, EXE, Java/.NET bytecode, APK) to understand the internal logic and thereby find the flag. The main goal of Reverse Engineering is not to exploit vulnerabilities, but to recover the algorithm, check conditions or hidden data in the program. Reverse Engineering challenges usually include analyzing native programs, analyzing bytecode or obfuscated/packed code. Players approach the problem through static analysis using disassembler/decompiler tools to read machine code and program structure, combined with dynamic analysis using debuggers to track execution flow and variable values when the program runs.
Decompiler is a tool used to convert an already-compiled program (binary) back into pseudocode, helping to analyze program logic when there is no source code. Some popular decompilers include IDA, Ghidra, Binary Ninja.
Open Source Intelligence (OSINT)
OSINT in CTF is a group of challenges focusing on collecting and analyzing information from publicly available sources on the Internet to find the flag. Unlike purely technical fields, OSINT does not require exploiting software vulnerabilities but relies on the ability to search, synthesize and infer information.
OSINT challenges usually provide a very limited amount of initial data, such as username, image, email address or website. From there, contestants must trace digital footprints through search engines, social networks, open databases, metadata, web archive history or other publicly available information sources to piece together data and determine the target information.
Example OSINT in CTF:
A typical OSINT challenge (shared in write-up) requires contestants to determine the geographic location of a provided photo and submit the flag as GPS coordinates or Google Maps link. The solving process includes the following steps:
1.	Contestants observe the provided image - for example, seeing a building with distinctive colours (orange, blue, white).
2.	The solver pastes the photo into Google/Yandex to find a website or similar image to find an article with a similar building image.
3.	Find detailed address from reference source: The page found describes the building and its location - belonging to this area and being one of Google’s offices.
4.	Search in Google Maps: With the area name and building, the contestant switches to Google Maps, searches for “Tottenham Court Road” → opens satellite map → guesses the photo location.
⇒ GPS coordinates identified: 51.51730173654459, -0.12462196379354945
Miscellaneous
Miscellaneous (Misc) in CTF is a combined category that includes challenges that do not belong to any single technical field such as Web, Pwn or Reverse. Misc challenges are usually related to OSINT, Encoding, Steganography, basic Forensics and logic puzzle challenges. This is a category suitable for beginners, helping to get familiar with analytical thinking, information search skills and creativity in information security.
2.1.2.2. Attack-Defense Format
This competition format follows the original classic CTF rules and is more difficult than other formats due to higher requirements. In addition to skills in finding security vulnerabilities and exploiting those vulnerabilities, players also need the ability to fix weaknesses, vulnerabilities, and protect their own systems against attacks from other teams. Another difference is the way points are calculated for competing teams. Points in this format are calculated based on different criteria such as: Attack points, defense points, bonus points, …
After the competition ends, the team with the highest score wins. This is the competition format closest to the real network security situation. Attackers perform attacks on the system while network administrators and security specialists have the task of resisting attacks from outside, while still ensuring the system’s operation…. The most famous competition about this format is DEF CON CTF.
This format can be hosted either online or locally on a shared LAN. As the name 'Attack & Defense' suggests, each participating team is assigned a server (known as a Team Box) that runs various services. All Team Boxes contain the same undisclosed security vulnerabilities. The goal of each team is to maintain the existing Services throughout the competition. Each team’s task is to find and patch the server’s vulnerabilities, while utilizing their knowledge of the vulnerabilities they have found to attack and affect other teams’ Services, bypassing the Services’ security mechanisms to capture the flag of each Service.
2.1.2.3. Hybrid Format
This is a combination of the two formats above, for example combining the attack-only format with different types of challenges. In this format, teams do not have their own servers, but instead teams will attack existing servers in the system; these servers also have vulnerabilities, and teams use their skills to find those vulnerabilities and use them to complete the tasks and challenges set by the organizers. Hybrid Format allows comprehensive assessment of participants’ capabilities, from analytical thinking, skill in solving challenges in each field, to the ability to operate, secure and respond to real attacks.
2.2. CTF Competition at FPT University
Over the years, CTF competitions have been regularly organized at FPT University on various scales and formats, from internal club competitions to school-level and nationwide competitions. The types of challenges used are not limited to the traditional Jeopardy model but also include the Attack-Defense format, depending on the training objectives and organization scale of each competition.
At the internal club level, CTF competitions are mainly organized with the goal of training skills for members. The scale of each competition usually ranges from about 10 to 15 teams, each team consisting of about 5 members. With this scale, CTF is used as a practical training tool, helping members practice technical skills, team coordination and get familiar with competition pressure in a real information security environment.
At a larger level, FPTU SecAthon is a specialized information security competition organized by FPT University, aimed at students from universities, academies and colleges nationwide. The competition is built according to the CTF Jeopardy model (Capture The Flag), a popular competition format in the international security community. In this model, teams must solve independent challenges in many different areas of information security knowledge, including cryptography, reverse engineering, web application vulnerability exploitation, digital investigation, binary exploitation and miscellaneous problems. Through directly analyzing systems, exploiting vulnerabilities and collecting “flags”, contestants are trained in attack-defense thinking as well as the ability to apply theoretical knowledge to real situations.
The motivation for contestants to participate in SecAthon lies not only in the prize factor but also in reputation, professional level and competition among schools. The target audience of the competition is students passionate about the field of information security, regardless of training school or year of study. FPT University maintains organizing school-level CTF competitions with an average frequency of once per year, while the EHC club organizes internal competitions about twice a year. This high organization frequency shows that the demand for using the CTF platform in training and competition at the school is very large and continuous.
The competition time for CTF competitions at the school usually lasts about 5 hours for focused competitions. In recent years, especially in 2025, the scale and scope of organization of SecAthon has been expanded from internal competitions at FPT University campuses to a format allowing students from universities, academies and colleges nationwide to participate. This expansion has significantly increased the number of competing teams, system access traffic and the complexity of competition infrastructure operation.
Along with competition activities, the organizers and club also set the desire to build a dedicated CTF system for the school. This system not only serves competitions but also acts as a repository of exam questions over the years, and can be integrated into specialized subjects to build practical lab exercises for students. In reality, current CTF platforms mainly serve short-term competition purposes and have not been effectively exploited in the role of supporting long-term teaching and training.
From the actual competition organization needs, an important requirement for the CTF system is the ability to open multiple challenge instances simultaneously for competing teams. Each team needs the ability to open multiple challenges at the same time, allowing team members to solve different challenges in parallel, thereby ensuring progress and competition experience. This is especially important for competitions with long duration and large numbers of challenges.
The long-term goal of CTF competitions at FPT University is not only to organize competitions but also to detect and train talents in the cybersecurity field. Through CTF, the school and club can select outstanding students for in-depth training, participate in future research and development projects, as well as build teams to participate in domestic and international cybersecurity competitions. These activities contribute to enhancing the reputation of FPT University in information security training and open up many career opportunities for contestants at large corporations and cybersecurity companies.
Currently, CTF competitions in the EHC club mainly use popular platforms such as CTFd, GZCTF or some commercial products originating from China. These platforms generally meet well in terms of user experience and basic functions; however, they often require relatively large copyright fees and are limited in the number of instances that can be deployed simultaneously. Previously, the club used a customized CTFd version, but to meet specific needs, members still had to self-develop many supporting plugins, increasing maintenance costs and system complexity.
From a technical perspective, the most important requirement for the CTF competition system is stability throughout the competition process, especially for competitions that run continuously, possibly up to two days. The organizers desire the system to achieve zero downtime even when source code updates are needed; in case of force majeure, the maximum allowable downtime is only 1-2 minutes to ensure contestant experience and the school’s reputation. In addition, the issue of exam question security is placed first, including ensuring the integrity of challenges when deployed, preventing the risk of answer leakage and avoiding forms of cheating during the competition.
Besides core technical and security requirements, the future CTF system also needs to be improved in terms of interface and brand identity. The competition platform is expected to carry the distinctive identity of FPT University, thereby contributing to building the image and reputation in the information security community.
3. Existing Systems
3.1. Overview of previous FCTF versions
The F-CTF system has been built and developed through many stages to meet the needs of organizing information security competitions in the university environment, especially serving training and competition activities at FPT University. Through each version, the system has been continuously improved in terms of architecture, performance, scalability and stability.
In the initial stage (version 1), the system was developed with the goal of overcoming the limitations of traditional CTF platforms. F-CTF was designed according to a model of 4 subsystems including: Challenge Hosting Platform, Contestant Platform, Management Platform and Control Center Platform. This architecture helps clearly separate functions and permissions between user groups, including Administrators (Admin), Contestants (Contestant), Challenge Writers and Jury. The highlight of version 1 is the automation of the challenge deployment process through Kubernetes/kCTF, providing a separate competition environment for each team, while replacing the manual storage method with a centralized system. As a result, the system initially ensured security, fairness and stable operation. However, version 1 still had many limitations, especially in resource management and system monitoring. Specifically, the system did not have a mechanism to limit the number of environments each team could create, did not set CPU and RAM limits for pods, did not have a mechanism to reclaim unused resources, and the monitoring tool was still simple, mainly based on Metrics Server.
Based on the foundation of version 1, version 2 focused on improving performance, optimizing resources and enhancing monitoring capabilities. The development team performed maintenance and re-testing of the entire system, fixing Kubernetes API integration errors, improving the interface and adding clearer error handling mechanisms. Key improvements in version 2 included integrating Redis to store and cache challenge environment information, implementing a Semaphore mechanism to limit the number of environments created simultaneously, checking the existence of the environment before creating a new one to avoid wasting resources, and automatically deleting the environment at the end of the competition. In addition, the monitoring system was comprehensively upgraded through integration of Prometheus and Grafana, helping to monitor resources, logs and system status in real time. The system also added visualization functions for competition progress and improved emergency notification mechanisms for contestants, contributing to enhancing user experience.
Version 3 of F-CTF continued to be developed to overcome the remaining issues of versions 1 and 2 after being run at Secathon2025. The operation process revealed many limitations in load capacity, resource allocation and stability when many users accessed simultaneously. On that basis, version 3 was developed and the system was restructured. One of the most important improvements was standardizing the infrastructure on the Kubernetes platform, unifying all services on a single container orchestration layer. The system moved from a monolithic architecture to a Microservices model, clearly separating the contestant system and the administration system, thereby minimizing bottlenecks and enhancing scalability. In terms of operation, the system applied an automated CI/CD process through Argo Workflows, helping to fully automate the challenge lifecycle from image building, deployment to resource recovery. At the same time, the system implemented atomic concurrent control using Redis Lua Script, aiming to eliminate Race Condition errors in the process of creating environments and submitting flags. In addition, user experience continued to be improved with features such as PDF challenge description support, visual deployment status display and real-time feedback. The system also built a two-way data synchronization mechanism with the original CTFd platform, ensuring continuity in case of infrastructure incidents.
Through three development stages, the F-CTF system has been continuously improved in terms of architecture, performance and operation. Version 1 laid the initial foundation with a four-subsystem model, automated challenge deployment and clear separation of user permissions; however, it still had limitations in resource management and monitoring. Version 2 focused on performance optimization, added resource control mechanisms through Redis and Semaphore, and upgraded the monitoring system with Prometheus and Grafana. By version 3, after the actual deployment of version 2 at SecAthon 2025, the system was comprehensively restructured towards Microservices, standardized on the Kubernetes platform and automated operation processes with CI/CD. Concurrent control mechanisms, user experience improvements and data synchronization were also enhanced.
3.2. Operating procedures
The operation process of the F-CTF system in version 3 is designed in a standardized and automated direction, including three main stages: pre-competition preparation, operation during the competition and post-competition processing. Compared to previous versions, which still depended heavily on manual intervention by the intermediate operation team (MrX), version 3 no longer has this role through completing the coordination mechanism and automating the deployment of competition environments.
In the preparation stage, the organizers develop an organization plan, assign personnel and establish official communication channels to support contestants throughout the competition time. The system is fully configured with operation parameters such as start time, end time and scoreboard freeze time. Challenges are compiled, tested and updated to the system with full information about content, scores, attached files, hints and related conditions.
In version 3, each challenge is standardized in the form of a directory containing Dockerfile and necessary configuration files. After completing the content, the challenge writer uploads the previously prepared challenge file. During the competition, when contestants initialize the practice environment, the system will automatically load the corresponding image and deploy it on the Kubernetes platform. Before the official competition day, the organizers conduct a comprehensive test of the entire operation process, including environment initialization, challenge access, flag submission and scoreboard update, to evaluate the system’s readiness in all cases.
During the competition, contestants access the Contestant Portal to select challenges, track progress and submit answers. For challenges that require a separate environment to be deployed, the system in version 3 automatically initializes through the coordination mechanism on Kubernetes, no longer depending on manual support from the intermediate operation team as in previous versions. Each challenge environment is independent containers allocated separately for each team, and is controlled in terms of resources, existence time and operating status to limit waste and resource conflicts. Teams can choose to participate in challenges randomly, however there are challenges that require solving certain challenges before access is possible, and there are challenges whose points will be reduced when teams sequentially solve them (dynamic challenges). Starting or ending a challenge can be performed automatically by team members. Note there is a time limit for challenges; when the time expires, the competition environment (challenge containers) will be automatically reclaimed and cannot be accessed.
Before the competition ends, the system activates the scoreboard freeze mechanism to ensure competitiveness and fairness among teams. During this period, submissions are still recorded and processed, however rankings are not publicly updated until the competition ends. When incidents occur, contestants can send support requests through the ticket system or official communication channels.
After the competition ends, the system automatically reclaims competition environments, releases resources and aggregates results. The official scoreboard is announced after the freeze period ends. All data related to users, submissions, system logs and resource status is stored for summarization, evaluation and reconciliation.
Based on the collected data, the organizers can analyze system performance, resource consumption, incidents and contestant feedback to propose improvements for subsequent competitions. This process contributes to maintaining continuity in improving the quality of platform operation.
In general, the operation process of F-CTF in version 3 has been redesigned towards automation and centralization. Standardizing challenges in container form, combined with the coordination mechanism on Kubernetes, helps the system strongly reduce dependence on the intermediate operation team, enhance load capacity, optimize resource management and ensure stability in large-scale competitions.
3.3. Legacy platform and functionality in the system
The F-CTF system started by being built based on inheriting and integrating two open-source platforms that have been proven in the Capture The Flag (CTF) community: CTFd and kCTF. CTFd is an open-source CTF framework developed in Python with Flask, aimed at providing a comprehensive solution for organizing, managing and operating CTF competitions. According to official documentation, CTFd is a platform that provides everything needed to operate a CTF, with high customizability through plugins and themes and focusing on ease of use as well as expansion.
In terms of functionality, CTFd supports organizers in creating and managing challenges, challenge categories, flags, and hints through an intuitive administration interface. The system allows defining flags in many different types, including static flags and regular expression (regex) flags, helping to meet many challenge types and different scoring requirements. CTFd also provides an automatically updated real-time scoreboard, supports hiding scores until the freeze time to prevent early result disclosure, and competition progress charts to help organizers and players track the match situation. The system also integrates mechanisms to prevent flag brute-force attempts and limits the number of attempts to ensure fairness and prevent abuse during flag submission. In addition, CTFd supports features such as SMTP/email management for user confirmation, password reset, along with the ability to import/export CTF data for storage and reuse for later events.
Meanwhile, kCTF is an open-source infrastructure platform developed by the Google Security team, designed to support the deployment, management and isolation of CTF challenges on the Kubernetes platform. According to kCTF’s official documentation, this is a Kubernetes-based infrastructure system for CTF competitions, helping organizers and challenge authors build, test and deploy challenges without requiring deep Kubernetes knowledge. Each challenge in kCTF is described by configuration files (YAML) specifying container image, resources, services, and network rules, from which Kubernetes automatically creates objects such as Deployment, Service and Ingress to create the competition environment.
A key point of kCTF is the use of sandboxing to isolate the competition environment. Specifically, kCTF uses nsjail, a mechanism to run challenges in a closed environment for each TCP connection, ensuring that contestant processes are isolated and do not affect each other, thereby enhancing safety and fairness in competition. In addition, kCTF provides quick and compact deployment documentation, in which challenges can be run in a few minutes with simple configuration or expanded thanks to the full features of Kubernetes such as autoscaling, health checks and integrated network services.
In general, CTFd and kCTF play the role of reference platforms and starting foundations in the process of forming the F-CTF system. Through successive development versions, especially in version 3, the system has been comprehensively redesigned in terms of architecture, functionality and operation process, thereby forming an independent platform with its own characteristics suitable for the academic environment and large-scale competitions. Selective inheritance of design principles from the two original platforms, combined with internal improvements, has created a solid technical foundation for the long-term development of F-CTF.
3.4. Customization compared to the original software
Although CTFd and kCTF provide important foundational functions for organizing and deploying Capture The Flag competitions, when applied in real-world environments with large scale, large numbers of users and complex operation requirements, these two systems still reveal certain limitations. On that basis, during the process of building F-CTF through the previous 3 versions, the development team has gradually performed customizations and expansions to more closely connect the competition management system and the container deployment platform. From the early versions, F-CTF added intermediate mechanisms to synchronize user data, challenge status and competition environment information, helping to reduce dependence on the original independent tools.
Through each version, the system was gradually adjusted to better suit real operation needs. In versions 1 and 2, improvements mainly focused on perfecting basic functions, optimizing performance and adding initial resource control mechanisms. These changes helped the system operate more stably, however they still did not fully meet requirements when the number of users increased.
By version 3, F-CTF had a clear improvement in architecture to enhance load capacity, increase stability and optimize resource usage. The system was standardized on the Kubernetes platform, gradually moving to a service separation model, while adding automation mechanisms in challenge environment deployment and recovery. Concurrent control, resource management and data synchronization were also perfected more, contributing to limiting incidents during the competition. Along with infrastructure changes, contestant interfaces and operation support tools were also adjusted and expanded through each version. In version 3, the system formed a separated frontend-backend model, making function expansion and maintenance more flexible. In addition, monitoring and system status tracking mechanisms were also tightly integrated, supporting the organizers in timely detection and handling of incidents.
In general, the improvements of F-CTF through the versions not only aimed to overcome the limitations of the original CTFd and kCTF but also changed to suit practical requirements in the training and information security competition organization environment. Especially, version 3 had major changes in architecture and operation, helping the system significantly enhance load capacity, resource management and stability, while creating a foundation for continued development in subsequent stages.
3.5. System features
3.5.1. Use case
The F-CTF system is designed to target four main user groups: Admin, Contestant, Jury, Challenge Writer. Each group has a clear role in the F-CTF system.
    
  Figure 2: Use case Diagram for Admin
Admin (Figure 2) is the user group with the highest privilege level, responsible for administering and operating the entire F-CTF system. This group performs user and team management through functions to create, update, delete, authenticate and lock/unlock accounts, further including features such as assigning captain rights to users in Team mode, creating rewards, viewing analysis information, IP addresses. Admins have the ability to send notifications to contestants, receive and handle technical support requests, and perform import/export of user data in CSV files as well as distribute login information via email. Admins have the right to delete invalid or rule-violating submissions or export data to files for storage or analysis.
In addition, Admins are responsible for configuring competition parameters such as start time, end time and scoreboard freeze period, and can adjust system settings when necessary. This group has full rights over all challenges, including creating, editing, deleting and deploying competition environments. In addition, Admins also monitor system status and operation logs to serve monitoring and incident handling. When needing to organize a new competition, Admins can delete all old competition data to prepare for the new competition.
Admins can also transfer and synchronize data between F-CTF and the original CTFd system to ensure backup, recovery and continuity in operation.
 
Figure 3: Use case Diagram for Contestant
Contestant (Figure 3) is the central user group, directly participating in solving challenges in the competition. Contestants can log into the system, access the challenge list and view detailed content of each challenge, including description documents in PDF format and related attached files and other parameters about points or time.
For challenges that require a separate deployed environment, contestants can initialize and stop isolated competition environments of challenges for their team through the system. During the competition, contestants perform flag submission to record scores, can unlock hints at the cost of corresponding points, track the scoreboard and receive notifications from the organizers.
When encountering technical incidents or difficulties in solving, contestants can send support requests through the ticket system and track processing history. In addition, users in this group can also manage personal information, view their own or team action logs, update profiles and change passwords to ensure account safety.
 
Figure 4: Use case Diagram for Jury
Jury (Figure 4) is the user group responsible for supervising and ensuring fairness and transparency throughout the competition process. This group monitors contestants’ progress through submitted flags, scoreboard information, thereby promptly detecting abnormal signs.
Jury has access to monitoring accounts, tracks progress and competition results of contestants to serve checking, reconciliation and detection of rule violations. In addition, Jury supports receiving, verifying and resolving complaints related to competition rules and fairness. This group also directly handles tickets reflecting on rules, results and competition behaviors that may be sent from Contestants.
 
Figure 5: Use case Diagram for Challenge Writer
Challenge Writer (Figure 5) is the user group responsible for designing, building and ensuring the quality of challenge content in the F-CTF system. This group has the right to create, edit and manage all information related to the challenges they are responsible for, including challenge name, description, score, challenge type, attached files, classification tags, hints, flags, challenge opening time, as well as prerequisite conditions for completing other challenges before access is possible.
During operation, Challenge Writers can flexibly update challenge attributes to suit the actual situation of the competition, while tracking the operating status and edit history of each challenge.
Challenge Writers are mainly responsible for creating challenges, needing to prepare full source code and Dockerfile according to standards for the challenge, upload the challenge zip file, the system will automatically build the image, store it on Docker Hub and be ready for environment initialization when contestants request. Challenges can be previewed and tested by Challenge Writers in an independent environment before official announcement, thereby limiting technical errors and issues arising during the competition.
