3.7. Remaining weaknesses of the FCTF system
Although previous versions of the FCTF system have met part of the requirements for organizing and operating information security competitions, and achieved some positive results in practical deployment at Secathon 2025, the overall assessment process from Version 1 to Version 3 shows that the system still has some limitations in architecture, performance, security, scalability and stability. Fully identifying these weaknesses is an important basis for the research, design and completion process of the system in Version 4.
3.7.1. Application Logic & Data Integrity Issues
3.7.1.1. Weakness in the Health Check mechanism during challenge deployment (IS-2)
In the current F-CTF system, the challenge environment initialization process is coordinated through Argo Workflows. When contestants perform the start challenge operation, the workflow will proceed with deployment steps such as creating pods, configuring services and returning the connection string (URL or host:port) to contestants immediately after the workflow ends with Succeeded status. However, the current success status of the workflow only reflects that the infrastructure-level deployment steps have been completed, but does not ensure that the application inside the pod is ready to serve real access.
To illustrate more clearly the deployment flow and the health check issue, the Sequence Diagram below describes in detail the process from when the contestant presses the "Start Challenge" button until the contestant can access the challenge environment, including interactions between Contestant Portal, Contestant BE, Deployment Center, Argo Controller, K8s API Server and Challenge Pod. The diagram highlights the core weakness: the system returns "Challenge Ready" to the contestant when the container is Running, but the application inside has not completed the initialization process, leading to Connection Refused status when the contestant tries to access immediately.
 Figure 9: Sequence diagram for Health Check Mechanism
By default, Kubernetes considers a pod running when the container inside has started and does not crash immediately. If there is no health check mechanism, Kubernetes cannot determine whether the container is truly ready to receive requests or not. This issue can be seen more clearly in applications that require long startup time where processing can only be performed after initialization is complete.
In addition, the current watcher code only relies on container-level status ("ContainerStatuses[].Ready") to determine that the pod is ready, instead of checking pod-level status ("PodCondition Ready=True"). According to Kubernetes Pod Lifecycle, a pod is only considered Ready when all containers inside are ready and readiness probes (if any) all return success. Checking only container status while ignoring pod condition makes the system possibly confuse between the container having started and the application being ready to serve.
Due to the lack of health check mechanism and inaccurate watcher logic, the system may return the connection string to contestants while the pod is still in internal startup status (initializing). The consequence is that when contestants access the provided address immediately, the web service has not responded or returns an error, and only after a certain time the web page can be accessed normally. From the user’s perspective, this creates a feeling that the system is operating unstably or has errors, although technically the deployment process is still proceeding correctly.
The table below illustrates the asynchrony between states in the pod startup process and the impact on user experience:
State	Symptom	Impact
Pod version = Running	Container has started	UI shows "Running"
ContainerStatuses[].Ready = true	Container reports ready	Watcher emits RUNNING
PodCondition Ready = false	Pod not yet ready	Service does not accept traffic
Contestant connects immediately	Request fail/timeout	User perceives a system error
Table 2: Effect of not having health check
The core cause of this issue lies in the current system not applying Kubernetes readiness probe mechanism to determine the real readiness status of the application. Implementing these probes requires the application in the container to provide a health check endpoint (for example /health or /ready) for Kubernetes to check. However, in the context of the system allowing many challenges developed by different authors, requiring all Challenge Writers to self-build and maintain health check endpoints significantly increases complexity and burden for question setters.
Therefore, the current system is inferring the service readiness status based on the completion status of infrastructure-level deployment steps, specifically the pod/container being successfully created and not falling into error status during startup. However, in Kubernetes, this status only reflects that the process in the container has been started, but does not guarantee that the application inside has completed the internal initialization process and is capable of receiving requests. Equating these two statuses creates a weakness in correctness in the deployment process, leading to asynchrony between the system’s “challenge ready” notification and the actual service accessibility. Although this limitation does not directly cause serious security risks, it significantly affects contestant experience and operation efficiency, especially in competitions with many simultaneous environment initialization requirements.
3.7.1.2. Recording contestant behavior logs depends on the client side (IS-3)
The system implements an Action Log mechanism to record important contestant behaviors during competition participation, such as opening challenges, opening hints, starting challenges or performing operations related to the challenge. These records are stored in the database and can be used for monitoring activities, analyzing user behavior or serving investigation when incidents occur.
However, the current logging mechanism depends on the frontend, in which the client actively sends a saveLog API request to the backend to save activity events. Since the frontend is outside the direct control scope of the system, users can modify client code, block requests or spoof log content. This makes log data not guarantee integrity and reliability, putting the system at risk of missing, inaccurate or manipulated actual contestant behaviors.
 
