3.7.2. Infrastructure & Configuration Weaknesses
3.7.2.1. Security risk from exposing challenge ports directly (IS-4)
Although F-CTF version 3 has switched to exposing challenges through Ingress and domain to enhance security in standard configuration, the current system still has a serious network security weakness in certain deployment scenarios, especially for challenges with special characteristics such as pwn challenges. In these cases, the challenge pod is forced to be exposed directly to the outside through the physical network ports of the node (for example NodePort or HostPort), instead of going through the centralized coordination and access control layer.
This approach leads to breaking the necessary isolation model. NodePort ports are usually in a fixed and easily guessable range (30000 - 32767), making them quickly scannable by popular tools. Therefore, a contestant can completely scan open ports on the node to detect and illegally access challenge pods that do not belong to their rights.
The consequence of this vulnerability is not only unauthorized access, but also opens up many attack scenarios that directly affect the fairness and reliability of the competition. A contestant can exploit other teams’ challenges early to obtain flags, intentionally send payloads to hang or sabotage services, interrupt the competition process, or interfere with the status of the challenge environment. In the context of pwn challenges that usually contain serious vulnerabilities by design, allowing uncontrolled network access further increases the risk of abuse.
In addition, because these connections go straight into the node and challenge pod, they completely bypass border layer protections such as Cloudflare and Nginx Ingress, including access filtering mechanisms, rate limiting and user identity recording. This makes the system not only lack network access control but also encounter difficulties in tracing the origin of violations or cheating behaviors. In worse cases, a successfully exploited challenge pod can become the starting point for lateral movement attacks to other pods or internal services in the same Kubernetes cluster.
3.7.2.2. Challenge pod isolation and privilege shortcomings (IS-5)
In the F-CTF system, each challenge is dynamically deployed through Kubernetes resources based on configuration files in YAML form, called challenge deployment templates. This template plays the role of a detailed technical description, regulating how the challenge is initialized in the cluster, including execution environment, network configuration, process permissions, resource access scope and accompanying security constraints.
Every challenge when deployed follows the same template, therefore the template becomes the central factor determining the safety level of the entire system. If the template is not tightly designed, challenges created from that template will have the ability to access or interact beyond the necessary scope, increasing risks to internal components of the system.
Pod Security Standards Framework
To evaluate the safety level of pod configuration, Kubernetes provides Pod Security Standards2 - a clearly defined set of policy levels to manage security aspects of pod specifications. Pod Security Standards define three main policy levels from the most open to the most restrictive:
●	Privileged: Completely open policy, without any constraints, usually used for system-level workloads managed by trusted users
●	Baseline: Minimum restrictive policy to prevent known privilege escalations, allowing default Pod configuration with basic safety level
●	Restricted: Strictest policy, complying with current best practices on Pod hardening, recommended for security-critical applications or lower-trust user environments
Baseline Policy Requirements
Baseline policy includes basic controls to prevent known privilege escalations:
●	Host Namespaces: Prohibit sharing host network, host PID, or host IPC namespaces
●	Privileged Containers: Prohibit containers running in privileged mode
●	Capabilities: Limit Linux capabilities that can be added
●	HostPath Volumes: Prohibit direct access to host filesystem
●	Host Ports: Prohibit or limit binding to host ports
●	AppArmor/SELinux: Require use of RuntimeDefault or allowed profiles
●	Seccomp: Must not be set to Unconfined
●	Sysctls: Only allow "safe" sysctls that have been namespaced
Restricted Policy Requirements
The Restricted policy is built upon the Baseline foundation and incorporates more stringent controls:
●	Volume Types: Only allow safe volume types (configMap, secret, emptyDir, persistentVolumeClaim, etc.)
●	Privilege Escalation: Must set allowPrivilegeEscalation: false
●	Running as Non-root: Must run containers with non-root user
●	Non-zero User ID: User ID must not be 0
●	Seccomp Profile: Must be explicitly configured to RuntimeDefault or Localhost
●	Capabilities Dropping: Must drop ALL capabilities, only add back NET_BIND_SERVICE if needed
●	Read-only Filesystem: Best practice requires root filesystem in read-only mode
Evaluation of Current Challenge Template according to Pod Security Standards
The current challenge deployment template uses Kubernetes’ default container runtime (runc), providing process-level isolation through Linux namespaces and cgroups. However, this mechanism still relies on the shared kernel model, in which the container shares the node host’s kernel directly and has no additional sandbox layer. When compared with Pod Security Standards, the template has not fully enforced constraints on process privileges and resource isolation, leading to many serious violations as detailed in the table below:
Pod Security Control	Configuration in Old Template	Violation and Impact
