Table 3: Table Evaluating Violations of Pod Security Standards of Old Template
When evaluating overall according to the Pod Security Standards Framework, the old challenge deployment template shows uneven compliance between policy levels, with some controls implemented correctly but still having many serious shortcomings.
On the positive side, the template has complied with some important controls of Baseline policy. Specifically, the template does not use dangerous privileged features such as Host Namespaces Sharing (hostNetwork, hostPID, hostIPC are all not enabled), does not allow Privileged Containers (privileged: false), and does not mount HostPath Volumes to access the host filesystem. The template also partially complies with Restricted policy requirements through disabling Privilege Escalation (allowPrivilegeEscalation: false) and dropping all Linux Capabilities (drop: ["ALL"]). In addition, disabling automountServiceAccountToken prevents containers from accessing the Kubernetes API server, minimizing the risk of privilege escalation through service account tokens.
However, although there are some basic compliance points, the template still does not achieve full compliance with any policy level of Pod Security Standards due to the following serious violations:
For Baseline Policy (minimum level), the template violates 3 important controls:
●	Seccomp Profile is not explicitly configured, leading to the pod running with Unconfined profile, allowing execution of all dangerous syscalls such as ptrace, mount, reboot
●	AppArmor/SELinux is not configured, lacking mandatory access control at kernel level
●	Pod Security Admission is not activated at namespace level, lacking automated enforcement mechanism
For Restricted Policy (recommended for untrusted workloads), in addition to 2 inherited violations from Baseline (Seccomp and AppArmor), the template also violates 1 additional serious control:
●	Running as Non-root is not enforced (runAsNonRoot and runAsUser are commented out), allowing containers to run with root user (UID 0) and have full privileges in container namespace
Besides violating Pod Security Standards, the template also does not comply with important security best practices:
●	Read-only Root Filesystem is not configured, allowing attackers to modify binaries and persist backdoors
●	Network Policy is not established, allowing unrestricted network access to every pod/service in the cluster
●	Host Ports Exposure via NodePort bypasses ingress controls and authentication layers
●	Runtime Class uses default runtime (runc) instead of sandboxed runtime for untrusted workloads
These unapplied security configurations, such as allowing containers to run with root privileges, not restricting system calls, and not controlling network access between pods, have significantly increased the attack surface of the system. In case a challenge pod is compromised, the attacker can take advantage of root privileges to perform dangerous behaviors, exploit operating system vulnerabilities, or move to other pods and services in the cluster. When many important protection layers are not established, the system’s multi-layer defense capability is reduced, thereby increasing the risk of serious attacks occurring.
