From the end-user perspective, contestants still had the ability to send new start challenge requests, however they continuously received timeout notifications. In reality, these requests were still sent to Argo for processing, while a series of other workflows were still in pending status, waiting to be executed. Running challenges were negatively affected and at risk of unwanted termination. Argo continued to wait for running workflows to run indefinitely, leading to subsequent requests not being processed. The entire workflow automation process was completely interrupted, requiring manual intervention and cluster restart, causing significant downtime and seriously affecting user experience as well as system reliability.
e, Root Cause Analysis
The incident originated from the combination of five main issues related to resource scheduling, workflow configuration, and resource priority & preemption mechanism in the K3s environment.
(1) Allowing Workload to run on K3s Server Node
K3s architecture characteristics:
Unlike standard Kubernetes, K3s uses the term "server node" instead of "master node" or "control plane node". The server node in K3s is designed with specific features, including running all control plane components (API server, scheduler, controller-manager) in a single process, by default configured as schedulable allowing regular application workloads to be deployed directly on the server node, integrated ready kubelet along with container runtime (containerd) and CNI plugin, and containing datastore in SQLite form for single-server configuration or embedded etcd for high availability setup.
Current status description:
The current cluster is operating with K3s default configuration, allowing regular application workloads, including both challenge pods and workflow pods, to be scheduled and executed directly on the server node. The server node is running core components in a single k3s server process, including kube-apiserver playing the role of the cluster’s main API server, kube-scheduler performing pod scheduling function, kube-controller-manager managing controllers, SQLite or embedded etcd taking the role of cluster state datastore, along with supporting components such as CoreDNS, metrics-server and service load balancer. In particular, Kubernetes by default allows Pods to consume nearly the entire node capacity, unless the administrator proactively reserves resources for system components (Reserve Compute Resources for System Daemons3).
To illustrate more clearly the mechanism of the incident when the system receives 1000 simultaneous requests, the Sequence Diagram below describes in detail the processing flow from when the contestant sends burst requests, through the Argo Server and Argo Workflow Controller processing, K8s API Server and Scheduler attempting to allocate resources, until the system falls into deadlock status. The diagram highlights four important stages: Burst Requests (1000 concurrent requests), Resource Exhaustion (workflows deadlock waiting for pods), System Stuck & Deadlock (cleanup job cannot run), and Contestant Impact (users waiting indefinitely). The diagram also clearly shows the core weaknesses including workflow pods with zero resource requests always accepted by the scheduler, challenge pods unable to be scheduled due to the cluster having exhausted resources, and cleanup mechanism being deadlocked due to no priority class to preempt lower priority pods.
 Figure 17: Argo Workflow Stuck When Exceeding Resources Sequence diagram 
Incident occurrence mechanism: Because K3s consolidates all control plane components in a single process, when system load increases and application workloads consume resources on the server node, a chain of events occurs in the following order. First, resource contention occurs on the server node, in which challenge pods and workflow pods compete for CPU and memory resources with the k3s server process. Because the k3s server process has no separate resource guarantees, all components in this process are affected simultaneously. Next, the control plane begins performance degradation, with kube-scheduler lacking CPU to handle pod placement decisions, kube-controller-manager experiencing delays in reconciliation loops, and API server responding slowly or timing out. Finally, cascading failures occur, in which the scheduler cannot schedule new pods, existing pods are not reconciled correctly, failures in the resource cleanup process lead to resource leaks, and the entire cluster falls into unresponsive or partially functional status.
(2) Start-challenge Workflow does not declare Resource Request and Timeout
Resource scheduling characteristics in K3s: K3s uses the standard kube-scheduler of Kubernetes, therefore the behavior of scheduling pods with zero resource requests is completely the same as standard K8s. Pods with resources.requests equal to 0 are always considered suitable to be created on any node, while the scheduler does not reserve resources for these pods. This leads to the node being able to be seriously over-committed with many zero-request pods, and there is no mechanism to prevent pod creation when the cluster is overloaded.
Current status description:
The start-challenge Workflow in Argo Workflows is defined with uncontrolled characteristics, specifically resources.requests.cpu set to 0 (no CPU requirement), resources.requests.memory also 0 (no memory requirement), and no activeDeadlineSeconds or other timeout mechanisms configured.
Incident occurrence mechanism in K3s:
The incident process begins from the workflow pod creation stage, in which the Argo controller creates the workflow pod with zero resource requests, causing the K3s scheduler to always accept this pod because it does not require resources, and the workflow pod is scheduled immediately, usually on the server node if there is no taint. Next, in the challenge pod deployment attempt stage, the workflow pod executes the kubectl apply command to create the challenge pod, however the challenge pod has actual resource requests, for example 100m CPU and 128Mi memory. In conditions where the cluster has exhausted resources, the K3s scheduler cannot find a suitable node and the challenge pod falls into Pending status. Because the workflow does not terminate, the workflow pod continues running because the process does not crash, Argo still considers the workflow "in progress", there is no timeout mechanism to fail the workflow, and the workflow waits indefinitely for the challenge pod to be scheduled. Finally, a resource exhaustion spiral occurs, in which many workflow instances accumulate in running status, the Argo controller consumes CPU and memory to track these workflows, the database (etcd or SQLite) contains state of hundreds of pending workflows, and the K3s server process is overloaded due to many watch connections and state queries.
(3) Cleanup CronJob cannot execute when Cluster lacks resources
Resource scheduling and priority in K3s: K3s fully supports Kubernetes PriorityClass and preemption mechanisms, however there are some important differences. Default scheduler behavior in K3s is completely the same as standard K8s, but there are no built-in additional priority classes besides system-cluster-critical and system-node-critical. Preemption only occurs in cases where there is a higher priority pod and no available resources, while K3s server components are protected by system priorities.
Current status description: Cleanup CronJob is designed to automatically clean up challenge pods periodically. In a cluster resource exhaustion situation, all nodes have reserved full CPU and memory, no capacity left for new pods. When the CronJob controller creates a cleanup pod in this condition, the cleanup pod cannot be scheduled due to lack of resources.
Incident occurrence mechanism: The incident process begins from the CronJob trigger stage, in which the Kubernetes CronJob controller (running inside the k3s server process) creates a new Job, the Job controller then creates a pod for the cleanup task, and this pod is submitted to the scheduler queue. Next is scheduling failure, when the scheduler evaluates all nodes and sees that all report insufficient allocatable resources, leading to pod status changing to Pending with reason Unschedulable and event FailedScheduling with message "0/N nodes available: insufficient cpu/memory". During this stage, preemption does not occur because the cleanup pod has no PriorityClass or has low priority, while challenge pods and workflow pods also have no PriorityClass, leading to all having default priority equal to 0. The scheduler therefore cannot decide which pod should be evicted, and the cleanup pod continues pending without preemption occurring. Finally, the system falls into deadlock state, in which challenge pods occupy resources, cleanup pod cannot run to clean up these challenge pods, and resources are not released.
Core cause: The core causes include no PriorityClass hierarchy to distinguish workload criticality, scheduler not authorized to preempt lower priority pods, lack of resource reservation for critical system tasks, and no guarantee mechanisms for cleanup operations.
(4) Argo Workflows timeout mechanisms do not work accurately when experiencing burst requests
Characteristics of Argo timeout mechanisms: Argo Workflows timeout mechanisms, including activeDeadlineSeconds, ttlStrategy and podGC, do not operate as real-time timers. Instead, timeout checking is performed through the Argo controller’s processing loop (controller reconciliation loop). In each loop, the controller will scan the list of workflows in the cluster, compare the current time with the workflow start time plus the deadline time. If a workflow is detected to have exceeded the allowed time, the controller will send a signal to terminate the corresponding workflow pod. Therefore, the actual timeout time depends on the processing speed of the controller.
Current status description: In the test with 1000 start challenge requests sent almost simultaneously, although activeDeadlineSeconds was configured as 120 seconds, many workflows in reality were not terminated after 2 minutes as expected. Instead, some workflows continued to exist in running status for much longer, in some cases up to about 20 minutes before being stopped.
Mechanism leading to timeout delay: When a large number of workflows are created at the same time, the system must process hundreds of workflow events in a short time. Creating many Workflow CRDs simultaneously increases the load on the API Server and Kubernetes datastore (etcd or SQLite). At the same time, the Argo controller must put these workflows into its internal processing queue (workqueue). Because the controller processes workflows in the queue step by step, when the number of workflows is too large, some workflows that have exceeded the deadline time but have not yet been checked by the controller in time. During this time, the workflow pods continue to exist until the controller processes them in the next loop.
Main cause: The main cause of this phenomenon is that Argo Workflows timeout mechanism is only checked when the controller processes the workflow in its loop, instead of being triggered by an accurate real-time timer. When the system receives burst requests with hundreds or thousands of workflows created at the same time, the controller’s processing queue becomes too long, causing timeout checking to be significantly delayed. Therefore, under high load conditions, workflow timeout is only ensured at the eventually enforced level, meaning the workflow will ultimately still be terminated when exceeding the configured time, but the actual time may be significantly later than the original timeout value. This increases the number of running workflows in the cluster and prolongs the system recovery time after large load periods.
(5) Orphaned pods due to Pending Workflows not managed by TTL
Characteristics of Argo timeout/TTL for Pending workflows: The activeDeadlineSeconds and ttlStrategy mechanisms in Argo Workflows are only effectively enforced after the workflow has changed to Running or Completed status. Workflows still in the Pending queue have no corresponding waiting time limit and can exist indefinitely in the workqueue when the cluster lacks resources.
Current status description:
When the contestant sends a start challenge request, the backend system records the request status into Redis with short TTL (for example 5 minutes) to manage the session lifecycle. At the same time, the corresponding Argo Workflow is submitted but falls into Pending status due to the cluster lacking resources. When the TTL in Redis expires, the session record is deleted and the backend considers the request expired, no longer tracking it. However the Pending workflow in Argo still exists independently and does not recognize that the corresponding application session has been invalidated.
Incident occurrence mechanism:
After the cluster is partially released of resources (due to manual cleanup or some workflows ending), the Argo controller continues to dispatch the Pending workflows in workqueue order. These orphaned workflows still run normally and create challenge pods even though there is no longer a valid session in Redis. The pods created by these orphaned workflows are called orphaned pods: they exist in reality in the cluster, consume CPU/memory, but have no valid owner/session in the backend’s business logic.
Consequences:
First, orphaned pods consume useless resources, directly reducing capacity for subsequent valid requests. Second, because there is no corresponding session in Redis, the cleanup CronJob and cleanup mechanisms based on business status do not recognize these pods as objects needing processing, causing them to possibly exist for a long time until manual intervention. Third, the contestant of the original request who received timeout at the frontend may retry and create a new valid workflow, while the ghost pod from the old request is still running, leading to the possibility of duplicate resource occupation for the same user. Finally, through many overload and recovery cycles, orphaned pods accumulate and create a degradation loop, in which each time the cluster recovers it is followed by a new batch of orphaned pods, quickly pushing the cluster back to resource exhaustion status.
Core cause:
The core cause lies in the phase difference in lifecycle between the two status systems: Redis manages sessions by independent TTL at the application layer, while Argo Workflows have no linking mechanism to react when the corresponding session has expired. The lack of TTL or queue timeout for Pending workflows creates a serious control gap in sudden load periods, leading to the possibility of orphaned workflows and orphaned pods occurring after the recovery phase.
3.7.2.4. Security Configuration Vulnerabilities (IS-7)
To ensure the security and reliability of the F-CTF system before putting it into operation, the team performed a security check process based on the Kubernetes Security Checklist1 - the official document provided by Kubernetes and popular integrated testing tools such as Trivy and Kubescape.
The Kubernetes Security Checklist is a comprehensive baseline checklist, including essential security check criteria for systems running on the Kubernetes platform. The Security Checklist for Kubernetes is a set of criteria and recommendations aimed at ensuring the system is configured according to the best security practices. The checklist does not aim to replace in-depth security measures, but serves as an initial reference framework to evaluate the safety level of the system. The checklist is built based on the practical experience of the Kubernetes community, cybersecurity organizations and cloud service providers. The checklist content is continuously updated to suit the development of the platform. This document is divided into main groups:
Category	Description
Authentication & Authorization	Check authentication mechanism, RBAC permissions
Network Security	Check NetworkPolicy, ingress/egress control, API exposure
Pod Security	Check Pod Security Standards, seccomp, resource limits
Pod Placement	Check node isolation, taint/toleration, runtime class
Secrets	Check encryption at rest, secret injection
Images	Check image security, unprivileged user
Admission Controllers	Check admission webhook, policy enforcement
Table 5: Kubernetes security check categories
To ensure comprehensive security effectiveness, we believe it is necessary to combine with automated evaluation tools that have been developed to strictly comply with safety criteria from security experts.
Regarding popular Kubernetes security standards:
●	CIS Kubernetes Benchmark: A standard set issued by the Center for Internet Security, providing safe configuration guidelines for components in the Kubernetes system. This standard is widely used in compliance assessment and security audit activities. The content focuses on protecting the control plane, nodes, RBAC mechanisms, audit logging and secret management, thereby helping to minimize risks arising from configuration errors.
●	NSA Kubernetes Hardening Guide: A hardening guideline document built by NSA and CISA, focusing on practical defense measures in container and cloud-native environments. This guide emphasizes reducing the attack surface, protecting the software supply chain, controlling access and enhancing monitoring to increase resilience against advanced threats.
●	Kubernetes Pod Security Standards (PSS): Security standard for Pods, including three levels: Privileged, Baseline and Restricted. In which, the Restricted level is recommended for production environments to limit container privileges and enhance system safety.
Based on the checklists and security standards presented, the FCTF system is implemented combining automated evaluation tools to check compliance level and detect early weaknesses in the operation process. In which, the two main tools used are Trivy and Kubescape, which are highly evaluated by the Kubernetes and information security community for reliability and check coverage:
●	Trivy: an open-source tool specialized in scanning security vulnerabilities and configuration deviations in container and Kubernetes environments. In the FCTF system, Trivy is used to perform scanning of published security vulnerabilities (CVE) in container images, detect Kubernetes configurations that do not comply with CIS Kubernetes Benchmark, and check container permissions and potential risk settings. Through comparing scan results with recommendations from CIS Benchmark, Trivy supports identifying configuration points that have not yet met security standards, thereby serving as a basis for system adjustment and optimization.
●	Kubescape: a comprehensive safety evaluation tool for the Kubernetes system. Kubescape focuses on checking compliance with popular security frameworks such as NSA/CISA Kubernetes Hardening Guide, MITRE ATT&CK and CIS Benchmark. This tool allows analyzing the entire cluster according to standardized security control groups, evaluating the application of Pod Security Standards, as well as identifying risks related to privilege escalation, service network exposure and secret management. Thanks to analysis capability at both configuration and behavior levels, Kubescape helps provide an overall view of the system’s security status, supporting appropriate improvement measures.
To have an objective and quantitative evaluation of the security level of the F-CTF system, an automated security check round was performed on the K3s Production cluster and the overall current YAML files to configure the system. The check process used two standard tools: Kubescape and Trivy, and combined with Manual Test through the Kubernetes Security Checklist.
Below are the results on the security level of the Kubernetes Cluster through evaluation and checking:
3.7.2.4.1 Kubernetes Cluster Misconfigurations - Trivy Scan Results
Scan results from Trivy on "cron-job" and "deployment" (for example: "image: bitnamilegacy/kubectl:1.33.4", "admin-mvc", "challenge-gateway") detected many serious violations related to Security Context configuration:
●	Root Filesystem Write Access (KSV014 - High Severity): Most important containers such as "cleaner" (in CronJob cleanup), "admin-mvc", and "challenge-gateway" are running without enabling "readOnlyRootFilesystem: true" mode. This allows attackers if they gain control of the container to overwrite system files, install malware or modify runtime configuration.
●	Default Security Context (KSV118 - High Severity): Containers are running with default Security Context, meaning they have no restrictions on privileges (Privileges). Trivy warns that this allows root privileges inside the container ("runAsNonRoot" is not set), opening the risk of privilege escalation if the node kernel has vulnerabilities.
●	Outdated Base Images: Using old images such as "bitnamilegacy/kubectl" contains many unpatched CVEs in system libraries (OS Packages).
3.7.2.4.2 Kubernetes Cluster Misconfigurations - Kubescape Scan Results
The report from Kubescape when scanning the entire cluster showed a very low compliance rate (Compliance Score) in many important control groups (Controls) belonging to the NSA/CISA Kubernetes Hardening Framework:
●	Non-root containers (C-0013 - Failed 19/19): 100% of containers (19 resources) are running with root user (UID 0). This is the most serious violation, because if the attacker escapes the container, they will immediately have root rights on the host node.
●	Immutable container filesystem (C-0017 - Failed 19/19): The entire workload allows writing data to the filesystem, violating the immutable principle of containers.
●	Liveness & Readiness Probes (C-0056, C-0018): 18/19 workloads lack Readiness Probe and 19/19 lack Liveness Probe. This not only affects reliability but is also marked by Kubescape as a risk to readiness.
●	Network Policies (C-0030): The system lacks Network Policies to isolate communication between pods. Kubescape warns that Ingress/Egress is not blocked allowing compromised pods to freely scan and attack other pods in the cluster.
●	Privileged Service Accounts (C-0034): Many Service Accounts are automatically mounted tokens into pods, creating opportunities for attackers to steal tokens to interact with the Kubernetes API Server.
In summary, the F-CTF system is operating with "open" default configuration, lacking deep protection layers, making the attack surface very large.
3.7.3. Application & Code-level Weaknesses
3.7.3.1. N+1 Query Problem (IS-8)
A weakness in the system’s database query design was found to be the N+1 query problem. The N+1 problem occurs when the system performs 1 initial query to retrieve data, but then for each element performs N additional queries, causing the number of queries to increase suddenly according to input data, leading to serious performance degradation and increased API latency.
