3.7.3.2. Dependency Injection Lifetime not suitable (IS-9)
In the old version, K8sService was registered with Scoped lifetime, causing each request to create a new service instance. When many contestants simultaneously start challenges, the system will generate many parallel connections to the Kubernetes API Server, easily causing overload and increasing memory usage, with potential risk of out-of-memory in long competitions.
In addition, the ScoreHelper class self-initializes DbContext in each method by injecting DbContextOptions and calling new AppDbContext(). This leads to creating many unnecessary DbContexts and database connections, putting pressure on the connection pool when the system processes many simultaneous requests. Although using is used, this design is still considered an anti-pattern in Entity Framework for high-load systems such as CTF.
3.7.3.3. Redis KEYS Command Blocking (IS-10)
In the old version, the system used the Redis KEYS command to query keys by pattern. This is a blocking command, causing Redis to have to scan the entire keyspace and pause processing other requests throughout the execution time. After obtaining the key list, the system continues to load all keys into memory and fetch all values in one StringGetAsync call.
This implementation causes many problems: the Redis server can be blocked for hundreds of milliseconds when the number of keys is large, causing the system to be temporarily “frozen”; loading all keys and values at once increases the risk of OutOfMemoryException and continuously triggers garbage collection; at the same time fetching data in one large request can cause timeout, exceed network buffer and have no ability to retry parts when errors occur. In addition, the system lacks an effective batch GET mechanism, forcing developers to handle many unnecessary round trips.
3.7.3.4. Missing CSRF Protection (IS-11)
In the current version of the F-CTF system, source code analysis shows that forms performing state-changing operations, especially administration and system configuration forms, have not implemented Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection mechanism. Specifically, requests sent from client to server via POST method do not include CSRF token or request origin authentication mechanism, causing the server to be unable to verify the validity of the request.
The main cause of this issue stems from the request processing mechanism design depending entirely on session authentication based on cookies, while lacking the step to check request integrity on the server side. Because the browser automatically attaches the session cookie in every request to the same domain, the system by default considers requests with valid sessions as legitimate without checking whether that request was actually initiated from the system interface or from an external source.
In addition, in some endpoints, the CSRF checking mechanism is disabled or bypassed through bypass configurations during previous development to serve compatibility with old APIs or simplify the integration process. The existence of endpoints that do not apply CSRF protection has weakened the overall defense layer of the system and expanded the attack surface.
3.7.3.5. Polling-based Deployment Monitoring & Code Quality Issues (IS-12)
In the old version, the system monitored the deployment status of challenge instances through a periodic polling mechanism, implemented by the GetPodsJob class. Instead of listening to state change events from Kubernetes, this service continuously sends requests to the Kubernetes API Server at fixed intervals to check the status of Pods. This mechanism leads to many serious problems: creating a large amount of redundant requests to the API Server even when no changes occur, increasing event detection latency due to dependence on the poll cycle, and causing unnecessary pressure on Kubernetes infrastructure in competitions with many contestants simultaneously starting challenges.
In addition, source code analysis also detected many other code quality issues. The system has service classes with inconsistent naming, causing difficulties in maintenance and expansion. Some controllers take on too many responsibilities, violating the Single Responsibility principle. In addition, the lack of a centralized GlobalExceptionFilter causes error handling to be scattered and inconsistent between endpoints, with potential risk of leaking internal error information to the outside.
3.7.3.6. Contest-state and prerequisite logic gaps in challenge file download (IS-13.1)
In version 3 design, the challenge file download flow focused mainly on token validity and did not enforce contest-state and challenge-state checks as a strict mandatory gate in the same request path. This created a logic weakness where file access could be served outside the intended competition context.
Specifically, the download flow lacked consistent denial rules for cases such as contest not started, contest ended, challenge hidden, or prerequisite dependency not satisfied by the current team. In some scenarios, if prerequisite data was malformed or validation failed unexpectedly, the logic did not always fail closed.
As a result, this issue is not a pure path traversal issue, but a business authorization weakness: contestants could gain file access in conditions that should have been blocked by contest and challenge rules.
3.7.3.7. Path traversal risk in challenge file download due to path handling and NFS mount scope (IS-13.2)
In version 3 design, the function to download attached files of challenges only performed contestant token validation before returning file content, while path handling remained exposed to manipulation.
After receiving a valid token, a contestant could intercept the download request and modify the path parameter. If backend path checks were not strict enough, the request could be redirected to other files in the same storage area.
The root cause was the combination of two factors: path input not being tightly constrained to a canonical allowlisted location, and backend container mounting an overly broad NFS directory scope. When the service read files directly from user-influenced paths, contestants who inferred directory structures (for example: challenges/<challenge_name>/flag.txt, description.md, or other resources) could attempt unauthorized file reads.
This leads to Path Manipulation / Path Traversal risk, where file access is no longer constrained to the exact file scope intended by the system.
3.7.3.8. Race condition in flag submit flow, unlock hint and challenge lifecycle (IS-14)
During source code analysis of the old system, the team noticed some issues related to handling multiple simultaneous requests appearing in the ContestantBE, ResourceShared and DeploymentListener components. These issues are not only in a specific endpoint but affect consistency between Redis and database, the status of challenges running on Kubernetes infrastructure, as well as the fairness of the competition when many contestants perform operations at the same time.
In the unlock hint function, the old version used a locking mechanism to protect data write operations when opening hints. However, the steps to check prerequisite conditions, check current points and check hint status were performed before the lock was applied. This creates a short time window in which multiple requests can pass the check step before the system begins writing data. When two unlock requests are sent almost simultaneously from the same user or team on different backends, both requests can pass the check step and then sequentially write data. As a result, the system may open the same hint multiple times or deduct points inaccurately if the data status changes in the time interval between the check step and the write step.
For dynamic challenges, the challenge’s score will change based on the number of teams that have solved the challenge. In the old version, recalculating the point value was not controlled when multiple requests ran simultaneously. When many correct submit requests occurred almost at the same time, the processing threads could read the same value of the number of teams that had solved before performing the calculation and recording the new point value. This could cause the final challenge point value to be overwritten by the later processed request, leading to the score not reflecting the correct number of teams that had solved at that time.
In the challenge lifecycle management process, an issue can occur when the user stops the challenge and then starts it again in a very short time. When the stop request is sent, the system updates the challenge status in Redis to DELETING to mark that the resources on Kubernetes are being reclaimed. However, deleting the pod and deployment on Kubernetes does not happen immediately but requires a period of time to complete. If during this time the user sends a start challenge request, the system will begin the process of creating a new deployment and update the corresponding status to Redis. However, when Kubernetes completes deleting the old lifecycle resources, the component listening to events from Kubernetes will update the Redis status to STOPPED. Because these two operations occur close in time and there is no mechanism to ensure update order, the STOPPED status from the previous stop process may overwrite the new status of the start process. This causes Redis to store incorrect status compared to reality and leads to the challenge not being able to start successfully even though the user has performed a valid start operation.
3.7.3.9. DeploymentListener sequential processing causes event backlog under high load (IS-15)
In the old version, the DeploymentListener component was not optimally designed for cases where many Kubernetes events occurred simultaneously. Status change events of pods were processed almost sequentially in a main thread. When the number of pod changes was large in a short time, these events could be piled up in the processing queue. This increased latency when updating RUNNING, STOPPED or DELETING status to Redis and database, thereby increasing the possibility of asynchrony between the system status and the actual status of resources on Kubernetes.
