The Submission screen in the current system still has many limitations, directly affecting the ability of Admin to monitor and process submissions during the CTF organization process. The system does not support a mechanism to filter submissions by team, user or specific time period, causing difficulty when needing to trace abnormal behavior or check results of a certain group of subjects. For dynamic challenges, there is no function to reset score when adjustment or incident handling is needed, reducing flexibility in competition operation. In addition, the data export function still has errors when exporting files according to correct/incorrect submission status, specifically the system exports all submissions when admin wants to export correct submissions, this affects the accuracy of reports. The system also does not allow Admin to proactively mark submissions as correct or incorrect in special cases requiring manual intervention, leading to limitations in handling complaints or arising situations.
3.7.4.6. Lack of mechanism to store and trace Challenge Instance history (IS-21)
Currently the monitoring function in the system only tracks the status of Challenge Instances when they are in running status in the Kubernetes cluster. The system is lacking a persistent storage mechanism to record the actual lifecycle history of Pods containing challenges. The current action log records only stop at recording the operation of pressing the "Start/Stop" button on the contestant interface, but do not accurately reflect the initialization and end events of the Pod itself at the K8s infrastructure layer. As soon as an instance is stopped, all its log information will not be stored again. This lack leads to admin being unable to compare between user operations and the actual infrastructure status, for example unable to know whether an instance could not be deployed due to the user actively operating or infrastructure error, in addition in post-competition work, the organizers have no historical data to evaluate the stability of challenges (which challenge is most often deploy-error), reducing the ability to optimize the system for future CTF seasons.
