Currently the system does not have an Audit Log mechanism to record and store the history of important operations performed by Admin, Jury or Challenge Writer. Changes related to user, team, challenge, system configuration or marking correct/incorrect submissions are not recorded in a centralized and systematic way. This leads to lack of tracing capability when incidents, disputes occur or when it is necessary to re-check the operation process of the organizers. The lack of search, filter and review history change mechanisms also reduces transparency, internal control capability and safety level in operating the CTF system.
3.7.4.8. Lack of mechanism to view Action Log for administrators (IS-23)
In the current system, the Action Log viewing function only allows Contestants to track their own actions and team members, while the competition Admin does not have a centralized access mechanism to monitor all user activities, leading to limitations in tracing incidents, detecting cheating and handling complaints. Important actions such as start challenge, stop challenge, correct or incorrect flag submission, unlock hint have not been centralized to serve checking and audit work.
3.7.4.9. Limitations in import & export function (IS-24)
The Import/Export function in admin config has not been working, affecting Admin’s data management efficiency. Specifically, the user, team, contest data export and import feature has not operated stably, generating errors during data processing, interrupting batch configuration operations. In addition, the system has not recorded and displayed detailed behaviors arising during import, for example cases of skipping (skip) existing users or teams, making it difficult for Admin to track processing results and compare data after performing operations. These limitations reduce transparency, increase data deviation risk and affect operation experience when organizing CTF competitions.
3.7.4.10. Limitations in bracket management and scoreboard display (IS-25)
The current system has allowed Admin to create and name brackets, however this function has not really demonstrated its value in actual competition operation. Specifically, although Admin can create brackets and assign contestants or teams to each bracket, the Contestant Portal does not integrate bracket data into the scoreboard interface at all. When viewing the ranking table, contestants only see the entire general list without the ability to filter or group according to the bracket they belong to. This makes the bracket feature meaningless in the context of competitions with many different segments, for example grouping by school, by school year, or by experience level. In addition, the system also does not have a configuration mechanism for Admin to control whether contestants are allowed to view results of other brackets or not, leading to a lack of flexibility in organizing competitions that require classifying competition subjects.
3.7.4.11. Lack of automated CI/CD process for system deployment (IS-26)
In previous versions, the F-CTF system did not have any automated continuous integration and deployment (CI/CD) process. When there were source code changes that needed to be put into the production environment, the operation team had to perform the entire manual process: determine which service needed rebuilding, run docker build command on local machine or directly on server, push image to Docker Hub, then SSH into server to run kubectl set image and kubectl rollout restart commands for each corresponding deployment. This process required the performer to clearly understand the entire system structure, remember the exact deployment name of each service, and perform the steps in the correct order without automatic checking. With a system consisting of many microservices such as ContestantPortal, ContestantBE, DeploymentCenter and AdminMVC, each time only one service needed updating still required a lot of time to perform manually and had high potential for errors, especially in the final preparation stage before the competition when many changes occurred simultaneously. The lack of CI/CD process significantly increased operation risks caused the development team to spend a lot of effort on repetitive tasks and reduced the frequency of being able to release patches without causing downtime or affecting system stability.
3.7.4.12. Challenge Management Weaknesses
a, Limitations in View Challenges and Search Challenges screen (IS-27)
In the current system, the challenge list does not provide sufficient important information to serve administration and competition operation, such as difficulty, creator, tags, deploy status and state. When the number of challenges increases, viewing only the basic list makes it difficult for Admin and Challenge Writer to quickly evaluate the characteristics of each challenge, difficult to detect hidden challenges, challenges that have been deployed or challenges with many related tags. In addition, the challenge search and filter function does not support combining multiple criteria such as category, type, name field, keyword, tags, difficulty, state and prerequisite, leading to administrators having to filter manually or switch through many different screens. This increases operation time, reduces administration efficiency and easily causes errors when having to process many challenges in the same contest.
b, Limitations in challenge deployment configuration (IS-28)
In the old version, the challenge deployment configuration screen only supported basic information such as expose port and deploy file, did not allow adjustment of important parameters related to resources and safety level of the running environment. The system did not support configuring CPU request/limit, memory request/limit, or limiting the maximum number of deploys for each challenge. Therefore, Challenge Writers had difficulty controlling the resource usage level of the pod and difficulty preventing cases where contestants continuously created instances beyond actual needs. When the competition had many challenges running simultaneously, this lack increased the risk of resource overload, affecting the stability of the cluster and consistency in the deployment process.
c, Lack of support for dynamic challenges and gradual point reduction mechanism (IS-29)
The current system does not fully support dynamic challenge type, in which the challenge value changes according to the number of correct submissions. Because there are no specialized interface and logic for dynamic challenges, Challenge Writers cannot customize attributes such as current value, initial value, decay function, decay value and minimum value. This makes the system only suitable for static challenges, while challenges that need a point reduction mechanism over time or according to the number of solvers cannot be correctly represented. The lack of dynamic scoring reduces the flexibility of the platform, limits the ability to design high-competition exam questions and does not correctly reflect the requirements of modern CTF competitions.
d, Lack of challenge version management mechanism (IS-30)
When Challenge Writers edit challenges, changes to Dockerfile, flag, description content, resources or deployment configuration can be applied directly without being saved as separate versions. This leads to the system not having version history to compare when it is necessary to check changes or find the cause of incidents arising after updates. If a new edit causes the challenge to have build or deploy errors, Challenge Writers cannot quickly review the previous stable version to compare configurations. The lack of version history mechanism reduces change tracing capability, causes difficulty in challenge maintenance process and increases the risk of interruption while the competition is running.
e, Lack of safe challenge version rollback process (IS-31)
Even when Challenge Writers realize that a new challenge version is causing errors, the old system still does not provide a clear and consistent rollback flow to quickly restore to stable status. Restoration usually must be performed manually by editing configuration files again, updating image tags or redeploying the challenge, so it is highly susceptible to errors and time-consuming under running contest conditions. In addition, because there is no rollback confirmation mechanism and synchronous redeployment, operators may accidentally return to a configuration that is not compatible with current data. This reduces the reliability of the system and makes challenge incidents handling slow and riskier than necessary.
f, Lack of Shared Instance challenge type support (IS-32)
The current system only supports a per-team instance model and lacks a mechanism for shared environmental challenges. This forces organizers to handle such cases manually or leads to resource waste. Therefore, a “Shared Instance” model should be introduced to support these scenarios.
3.7.4.13. Dependency on Docker Hub for service and challenge image registry (IS-33)
The current CI/CD build and deployment flow still relies on Docker Hub as the main registry for not only challenge images but also all core system service images (such as Contestant Portal, Admin MVC, Deployment Center, Gateway, etc.). This creates two practical limitations. First, Docker Hub's free private repository quota is limited to 20 GB, which is not sufficient for long-term operation when the system stores many challenge images, system service builds, versioned artifacts, and backups. Second, depending on a third-party public registry for core infrastructure components adds an external supply-chain dependency to a platform that needs strict control over image storage, access, and auditability. Any registry outage, rate limit, or credential exposure can delay both challenge deployment and system updates, weakening the overall security posture and stability of the competition platform. For these reasons, the image registry layer for the entire platform needs to be moved to a self-hosted solution.
3.8. Potential solutions
3.8.1. Application Logic & Data Integrity Issues
3.8.1.1. Improving the Health Check mechanism during challenge deployment
The health check mechanism during challenge deployment aims to ensure that the status reported by the system to contestants accurately reflects the actual accessibility of the service. In the current system, the Argo workflow ending successfully only ensures that the infrastructure-level deployment steps have been completed but does not confirm that the application inside the container is ready to serve requests. This leads to the system returning the connection string while the service is still starting, causing confusion and negatively affecting user experience.
To overcome this issue, the solution includes two complementary components:
a, Adding Readiness Probe to Pod Manifest (SOL-2.1)
Kubernetes provides a readiness probe mechanism that allows checking the readiness status of the application before marking the pod as Ready. There are two main implementation methods considered for the F-CTF system.
●	HTTP Endpoint Check: The application provides a health check endpoint (for example /health or /ready) for Kubernetes to send HTTP requests and confirm the application is ready when it receives a successful response. This is the method with the highest accuracy because the application itself determines the time it is ready to serve requests. However, this solution requires all Challenge Writers to add a health check endpoint in the application, which can significantly increase complexity and development burden in a CTF environment with many different authors.
●	TCP Socket Check: Kubernetes only checks the ability to establish a TCP connection to the service port. This method does not require any changes from Challenge Writers in the application; therefore, it is more suitable for the F-CTF context. Although this approach does not fully reflect the internal status of the application, it still helps ensure that the service is at a minimum level accessible from the contestant's side, eliminating basic connection errors such as CONNECTION_REFUSED.
b, Updating Pod Watcher Logic (SOL-2.2)
In addition to adding readiness probe, the watcher code needs to be adjusted to correctly check pod-level status instead of only relying on container status. Specifically, instead of only checking "ContainerStatuses[].Ready", the watcher needs to check the pod-level condition "PodCondition Ready=True". Only when this condition is satisfied does the backend emit RUNNING status and return the connection string to the contestant.
Combining these two components ensures that the system complies correctly with the Kubernetes Pod Lifecycle contract: the pod is only considered ready when all containers are ready and readiness probes (if any) all succeed. This eliminates the confusion between "container running" and "application ready to serve".
