3.8.2.2. Improving the isolation and privilege mechanism of challenges (SOL-5)
To overcome the Pod Security Standards violations stated, the challenge deployment template is redesigned to achieve compliance with Restricted policy level - the highest security level recommended for untrusted workloads. Improvements are implemented according to a defense-in-depth strategy, in which each independent protection layer has the ability to limit the impact scope (blast radius) of the challenge in case of exploitation, ensuring no impact on important components of the F-CTF system.
First, the new template proposes using sandbox runtime to add a safe isolation layer between the challenge container and the real kernel of the node host. Putting the challenge into a sandbox environment helps significantly reduce the risk of container escape and limit the impact of kernel-level vulnerabilities.
In terms of architecture, sandbox runtime differs from the default container runtime (runc). With runc, all containers on the same node share the host kernel directly according to the shared kernel model. When the application in the container performs a system call, this call is transmitted directly down to the real kernel of the host. This creates a large attack surface: if there is a vulnerability in the host kernel, the attacker only needs to exploit once to escape the container and take control of the entire node.
Sandbox runtime solves this problem with a higher-level isolation architecture, usually dual-kernel or syscall interception, in which each sandboxed container is provided with a separate processing environment. The core of this mechanism is the ability to intercept and handle all system calls from the container. When the application inside the challenge performs a syscall, instead of transmitting directly down to the host kernel, the runtime will handle and emulate the syscall in its own isolated environment or safely redirect the request. Only a very small set of safe and necessary syscalls are forwarded down to the real host kernel.
In addition, this mechanism also ensures tight management of all filesystem I/O operations, ensuring the container has no ability to directly access the host filesystem but must go through a controlled intermediate layer.
This mechanism significantly reduces the attack surface at the kernel level. In the runc model, the attacker only needs to exploit one vulnerability in the host kernel to perform container escape. With sandbox runtime, the attacker must overcome the sandbox protection layer before being able to access the host kernel - a much more complex requirement. The sandbox environment itself is also enhanced with seccomp-bpf, namespaces and cgroups mechanisms, while completely prohibiting dangerous syscalls.
