Table 9: Comparison of Container Runtime - runc vs Sandboxed Runtime
Although sandboxed runtime has performance overhead due to syscall interception and emulation mechanism, this is a completely acceptable trade-off in the CTF system context. Challenges have short lifecycles (from a few minutes to a few hours), low resource requirements, and workloads are mainly I/O bound rather than CPU intensive. More importantly, in a CTF environment where challenges are intentionally designed to contain vulnerabilities for contestants to exploit, tight isolation at the kernel level becomes a mandatory requirement to protect the system’s infrastructure.
Along with that, the new template strictly enforces the principle of least privilege. Challenges are forced to run under non-root user with clearly specified UID, while eliminating the possibility of privilege escalation. The root filesystem is set to read-only mode, ensuring the process inside the container cannot change system files or install persistence mechanisms. Removing all Linux capabilities continues to narrow the set of rights the challenge can use.
To reduce the attack surface at the kernel level, the new template applies Kubernetes’ default seccomp profile to limit the set of syscalls allowed to be called. This mechanism helps eliminate unnecessary syscalls for the challenge logic, thereby reducing the ability to exploit potential kernel vulnerabilities without affecting the normal function of the challenge.
In addition, the new template also applies AppArmor profile in RuntimeDefault mode, adding a mandatory access control mechanism at kernel level to limit file access capability and process interactions. The system also strictly limits the types of volumes allowed to be mounted into the pod, only allowing safe types such as ConfigMap, Secret, EmptyDir and PersistentVolumeClaim, while completely prohibiting HostPath volumes to prevent direct access to the node host filesystem.
In addition, security policies at the namespace level are also applied to control the behavior and communication scope of challenges. Pod Security Standards at restricted level are enforced to ensure every pod in the namespace complies with strict security constraints. NetworkPolicy is configured according to the default deny-all model, only allowing the minimum necessary communication flows, thereby preventing the challenge from illegally accessing the database and internal services of the system.
