3.8.2.3. Load control and workflow stability by resource allocation and priority mechanism
a. Solutions
To completely overcome the issues analyzed in section 3.7.2.3, the F-CTF system has implemented four main solutions to ensure self-recovery capability and stable operation under high load conditions.
Solution 1: Isolate Control Plane by Node Taints (SOL-6.1)
Problem solved: Prevent application workloads from competing for resources with control plane components, avoiding control plane degradation when the system is under high load.
Solution principle: Apply taint mechanism to K3s server node to prevent regular workloads from being scheduled to this node. Only system components with suitable toleration are allowed to run on the master node. This ensures CPU and Memory resources are always available for core components such as etcd, API server, scheduler, and controller-manager.
Reason necessary in K3s environment: Because K3s does not support system-reserved or kube-reserved configurations like standard Kubernetes, applying taint to the control-plane node becomes the only and mandatory measure to protect core components from resource shortage. This is an important best practice in production environments when using K3s.
Expected effectiveness: When application workloads cannot be scheduled to the master node, control plane components will not compete for resources. This ensures the scheduler has enough CPU to handle pod placement decisions, controller-manager can perform reconciliation loops on time, and API server always responds quickly. The system avoids cascading failures when the cluster is under high load.
Solution 2: Control Workflow lifecycle with Resource Requests and Timeout (SOL-6.2)
Problem solved: Prevent workflows from running indefinitely and ensure the scheduler has accurate information about resource needs to make appropriate scheduling decisions.
Solution principle: This solution includes two complementary parts. First, clearly declare resource requests and limits for workflow pods, helping the scheduler know exactly the number of resources needed and only schedule the pod when the node has enough available resources. Second, establish timeout mechanism through activeDeadlineSeconds so that the workflow automatically terminates after a determined period if it is not complete.
Mechanism of Resource Requests: When the workflow pod declares resource requests, the scheduler will only schedule the pod to the node when that node has enough unreserved resources. This creates a natural backpressure mechanism - workflows will be in pending status instead of being accepted and then running indefinitely under resource shortage conditions. The scheduler could reject workflows when the cluster is overloaded, preventing serious over-commit.
Mechanism of Timeout: Timeout mechanism ensures workflows cannot run indefinitely when encountering abnormal situations such as challenge pods not being schedulable. After the timeout period, the workflow automatically terminates and releases resources, reducing pressure on the Argo controller and database. This is an important fail-fast mechanism helping the system self-recover.
Expected effectiveness: With resource requests, the scheduler can make accurate decisions and workflows do not accumulate indefinitely in running status. With timeout, deadlock workflows will automatically terminate and release resources. The system avoids resource exhaustion spiral and significantly reduces the number of workflows that need to be tracked by the Argo controller.
Solution 3: Establish Priority & Preemption Policy (SOL-6.3)
Problem solved: Ensure important tasks such as cleanup jobs and system services always have the ability to reclaim resources from lower-priority workloads, avoiding deadlock when the cluster runs out of resources.
Solution principle: Establish a priority hierarchy (PriorityClass hierarchy) for different types of workloads in the cluster. Cleanup jobs and system services are assigned the highest priority level, Argo workflow pods have medium priority, and challenge pods have the lowest priority. When the cluster is full of resources and there is a high-priority pod that needs to be scheduled, the scheduler is authorized to evict lower-priority pods.
Preemption Mechanism: When a cleanup job needs to be scheduled but all nodes have reserved full capacity, the scheduler will search for lower-priority pods currently running on the cluster. The scheduler then evicts challenge pods (with the lowest priority) to release resources, then schedules the cleanup job into the newly released resources. After being scheduled, the cleanup job will execute the task of cleaning up expired challenge pods, continuing to release more resources for the system.
Breaking Deadlock: The priority and preemption mechanism breaks the important resource deadlock loop: previously, challenge pods occupied resources and cleanup pods could not run to clean them up. With preemption policy, cleanup jobs have the right to reclaim resources from challenge pods, ensuring the cleanup process can always occur even when the cluster is full.
Expected effectiveness: The system could automatically clean up resources without manual intervention. Important tasks such as cleanup jobs and system services are not affected by the resource exhaustion status of the cluster. The system avoids deadlock state and maintains continuous self-recovery capability.
Solution 4: Implementing Request Queue between DeploymentCenter and Argo Workflows (SOL-6.4)
Problem solved: Control the speed of submitting workflows to Argo to avoid overloading etcd and Argo controller, ensure timeout mechanisms operate accurately according to design and the system has self-recovery capability.
Problem context: In the initial stress test, although workflow timeout was configured for two minutes, workflows took up to twenty minutes to timeout. The cause was when one thousand workflows were submitted at the same time, etcd and Argo controller were seriously overloaded. Argo timeout is not a real-time timer but is enforced through the controller reconciliation loop - when the controller is congested, workflows that have expired must wait until the controller is free to be processed.
Solution: Build a message queue (RabbitMQ) placed between DeploymentCenter API and Argo Workflows, acting as a buffer and concurrency regulator. Instead of accepting all requests and submitting directly to Argo, the system puts requests into the queue and uses workers to process with tightly controlled concurrency.
Concurrency Control Mechanism:
Worker implements hybrid control strategy including two protection layers:
●	Primary: Concurrency-based control
a.	Worker queries the number of Running workflows in Argo before each submission
b.	Only submits when current_running < 30
c.	Ensures Argo is never overloaded, workqueue always at stable level
●	Secondary: Rate limiting protection
a.	Worker does not submit more than 10 workflows/second even if there are empty slots
b.	Prevents etcd write spike if many workflows complete simultaneously
●	Circuit breaker protection:
a.	If Argo query fails 3 consecutive times, worker pauses submissions for 60 seconds
b.	Allows Argo controller recovery after batch cleanup events
c.	Explanation of 20-minute downtime observed in Test 2
Comparison before and after: Before having the queue, one thousand workflow CRDs created simultaneously caused etcd write spike, informer lag, and controller backlog, leading to timeout being processed late by tens of minutes. After having the queue with rate limiting, workflows were submitted at controlled speed, etcd write stable, controller reconciled on time, and timeout mechanisms operated accurately according to configuration.
Additional benefits: Besides ensuring timeout operates accurately, the queue also brings better observability - queue depth, processing rate can be observed, and throughput adjusted according to real-time metrics. The system also has graceful degradation capability - handling burst traffic without paralyzing the control plane. The queue can also implement retry logic with exponential backoff when Argo returns resource quota exceeded error.
Expected effectiveness: Argo controller and etcd operate within design limits, not overloaded. Timeout mechanisms such as activeDeadlineSeconds and podGC are enforced at the configured time. The system could handle burst traffic in a stable way without affecting the accuracy of workflow lifecycle management mechanisms.
b. Summary of solutions
The proposed solutions do not aim to increase the total resources of the cluster, but focus on using resources in a controlled way and following Kubernetes best practices under real K3s conditions.
Control plane isolation helps eliminate the risk of the cluster hanging due to lack of resources for core components. Resource and timeout control for workflows helps prevent workflows from hanging indefinitely and reduces accumulated pressure on the system. Priority and preemption mechanism ensures that life-critical tasks, especially resource cleanup, always could be executed, thereby avoiding resource deadlock loops. Request queue ensures controller-based mechanisms operate correctly according to design by preventing overload from the beginning.
Although these solutions increase complexity in system configuration and operation, they are evaluated as necessary and suitable for the scale and characteristics of F-CTF. When implemented synchronously, these measures help the system change from “permanently hanging when overloaded” status to “automatic self-recovery” status, meeting production operation requirements for the F-CTF platform.
3.8.2.4. Proposed for Configuration Security & Hardening (SOL-7)
To overcome configuration vulnerabilities and violations of security standards that have been detected by Kubescape and Trivy, a comprehensive “Hardening” strategy needs to be applied to Kubernetes Manifests.
Enforce Security Context (Pod Hardening):
●	Set "runAsNonRoot: true" and "runAsUser: <UID>" (for example: UID 1000) for all containers to prevent running under root privileges.
●	Enable "readOnlyRootFilesystem: true" to prevent overwriting system files.
●	Configure "capabilities.drop: ["ALL"]" to remove all unnecessary Linux privileges.
Deploy Network Policies (using Calico or Cilium) to apply Zero-trust model:
●	Default Deny-All: Block all traffic between pods by default.
●	Allow-list: Only allow traffic through specific ports between authenticated microservices (for example: "admin-mvc" is only allowed to call "database" through port 5432).
●	Egress Control: Block connections to the Internet from unnecessary pods to prevent malware download or data exfiltration.
Automated Policy Enforcement: Use Kyverno or OPA Gatekeeper as Admission Controller in the cluster. Configure these policies to automatically reject Pod creation requests if they violate security rules (for example: no resource limit, running as root, mounting host path), ensuring the cluster always complies with NSA/CISA standards right from the input.
3.8.3. Refactoring Code to Eliminate Anti-patterns
3.8.3.1. Overcoming N+1 query error (SOL-8)
For the N+1 Query Problem, the core solution is to eliminate performing database queries inside the loop processing each Challenge. Instead, the system performs a pre-query for all related data (for example solve status of team or user) with a fixed number of queries, then stores the results in in-memory data structures such as HashSet or Dictionary for quick lookup. This approach helps reduce the number of queries from the 1 + N model down to only 1-2 queries, significantly improving performance and reducing API latency. In addition, using projection, JOIN or subquery directly in SQL queries can also be applied so that the database processes data relationships in a more optimal way.
3.8.3.2. Fixing DI Lifetime and DbContext management error (SOL-9)
For the DI Lifetime Scope issue, the system needs to be adjusted in the way services are registered and used that consume heavy resources. Services communicating with the Kubernetes API are changed to a reuse connection or controlled singleton model, avoiding creating many new instances and many unnecessary parallel connections. At the same time, business classes such as ScoreHelper are refactored to directly inject DbContext through Dependency Injection, allowing the DI container to manage the context lifecycle according to the request. This method helps reduce the number of database connections created, limits pressure on the connection pool and eliminates the popular anti-pattern in Entity Framework for high-load systems such as CTF.
3.8.3.3. Optimizing Redis access (SOL-10)
For Redis KEYS Command Blocking, the system needs to completely replace the use of the KEYS command with a non-blocking keyspace scanning mechanism based on SCAN with pagination. Cache data is processed in batches with limited size, avoiding loading all keys and values into memory at once. In addition, the system adds batch GET methods to retrieve multiple cache values in only one round trip, reducing the number of requests to Redis and increasing load capacity when the dataset is large or concurrent access is high.
3.8.3.4. Implementing CSRF protection mechanism (SOL-11)
First, the system needs to add a CSRF token mechanism for all forms using the POST method. Each user session is assigned a unique token generated by the server and embedded in the form as a hidden field. The server will authenticate the token when receiving the request and reject invalid requests with HTTP 403 error code, ensuring only valid requests from the system interface are processed.
In addition, endpoints using the CSRF bypass mechanism need to be reviewed and removed to reduce the attack surface and ensure consistency in security policy. The system also needs to configure the SameSite=Strict attribute for session cookies to prevent the browser from sending cookies in requests from external domains, thereby minimizing the risk of CSRF exploitation. At the same time, legacy APIs that are no longer used need to be removed or access limited through session control mechanism and endpoint whitelist to enhance access control and system protection.
3.8.3.5. Event-Driven Monitoring and Code Quality Standardization (SOL-12)
To overcome the inefficiency of periodic polling, a feasible method is to switch to an event-driven watching model by using the Kubernetes Informer/Watcher API - a mechanism that allows the service to register to listen to Pod status change events directly from Kubernetes instead of proactively sending requests at fixed intervals. This approach helps the system only consume resources when real events occur, significantly reducing the number of unnecessary requests to the API Server, while shortening status detection latency compared to polling which is limited by the fixed cycle.
To overcome code quality issues, a feasible method is to strictly apply SOLID principles and standardize naming convention according to a unified agreement throughout the project. Specifically, separating responsibilities between classes through the Single Responsibility Principle helps each service only handle one group of business, making it easier to test and maintain. In addition, adding a centralized GlobalExceptionFilter helps unify error handling and return across the entire system, avoiding the situation where each controller handles errors in its own way which easily leads to leaking internal information. Compared to the old design, this approach makes the codebase easier to read, easier for new members to onboard, and minimizes the risk of potential bugs arising due to duplicated or scattered logic.
3.8.3.6. Enforcing contest-state and prerequisite checks in file download flow (SOL-13)
To address IS-12.1, the file download endpoint needs a strict business authorization gate before any file read operation is executed. The system must reject requests when the contest has not started, has ended, or is in a non-access state by policy.
For challenge files, the endpoint must also block access if challenge visibility is hidden for contestants or if prerequisite challenges have not been completed by the requesting team. If prerequisite metadata is malformed, missing, or fails validation, the endpoint must apply fail-closed behavior (deny-by-default) instead of continuing the request.
With this approach, file delivery becomes bound to the real competition context, eliminating logic bypass cases where valid token alone could still lead to invalid file access.
3.8.3.7. Implementing multi-layer path control in the file download function (SOL-13.2)
To overcome the path manipulation vulnerability in the challenge file download function, the system can implement three independent control layers for the file download request processing method, in which each layer acts as a separate defense barrier, ensuring that even if one layer is bypassed, the remaining layers still maintain the safety of the system.
The first layer is path prefix checking: immediately after token authentication, the system checks whether the path parameter starts with the string "file/" or not (case-insensitive comparison). Any path that does not satisfy this condition is immediately rejected, thereby limiting the entire access scope to only the specified subdirectory inside the NFS mount, excluding all paths pointing to other storage areas that may contain more sensitive data.
The second layer is database-based path authentication or database whitelist: the token is expanded to carry additional file_id, and the database query is designed to require both conditions f.Location == path and f.Id == fileToken.file_id to be satisfied simultaneously. This mechanism has core security meaning: only paths that have been pre-registered in the Files table and match the file for which the token was issued can be allowed access; any arbitrary path created by the contestant themselves cannot pass this step even if syntactically valid.
The third layer is business-based access control: for files belonging to challenge type, the system performs two additional logical checks. First, reject if the corresponding challenge is in hidden status. Next, verify whether the contestant’s team has completed enough prerequisite challenges or not based on the team’s solved list in the database. If the challenge’s requirements JSON string has syntax error, the system defaults to deny-safe, avoiding error analysis leading to granting unintended rights. Overall these three control layers ensure that contestants can only download the exact file for which their token was issued, in the correct competition context and only when business conditions have been fully satisfied.
The fourth layer is infrastructure isolation at Kubernetes volume level: the deployment configuration of the contestant-be service is adjusted to no longer mount the entire root NFS directory into the container, instead only mounting the exact subdirectory that the application is allowed to access via subPath: file (corresponding to mountPath: /mnt/nfs/data/file), while setting the volume in readOnly: true mode. This protection layer operates completely independently of application source code and is at the kernel/OS layer: even if the application is exploited or misconfigured, the process inside the container physically cannot see any content outside the file/ directory of NFS and also cannot overwrite any file on NFS. This is the most important defense-in-depth protection layer because it eliminates the attack surface at the infrastructure layer instead of only relying on checks in code. Overall, these four control layers ensure that contestants can only download the exact file for which their token was issued, in the correct competition context, only when business conditions have been fully satisfied, and even in the scenario where the application is compromised, the container cannot go beyond the physical limits established by the infrastructure.
3.8.3.8. Overcoming race condition in challenge lifecycle by distributed locks, status control and parallel processing (SOL-14)
To overcome the above issues, changes in the system not only focus on fixing errors in individual endpoints but also adjust the way the system processes the entire lifecycle of challenges. Improvements focus on three main directions: increasing safety level for important operations, tighter control of deployment lifecycle, and improving concurrent processing capability of infrastructure status monitoring components.
For the unlock hint function, a feasible solution is to expand the scope of the existing Redis lock to cover both the prerequisite condition checking step and hint status before writing data. When a request starts processing the unlock operation, the system can hold the lock corresponding to the user or team throughout the process of checking and updating data. Other requests must wait until the lock is released. This approach helps ensure that prerequisite checks, hint status and player points are performed on the latest data, avoiding situations where multiple requests pass the check step and write data almost simultaneously.
For dynamic challenges, recalculating the point value can be protected by a distributed lock according to challengeId. Before reading the number of teams that have solved the challenge and updating the point value again, the system can temporarily hold the lock corresponding to that challenge. This helps ensure that at any one time only one process performs the point calculation, thereby avoiding cases where multiple requests read old data and then overwrite each other’s results.
In the challenge stopping flow, another solution is to apply a distributed lock according to the team-challenge pair to ensure each deployment has only one stop process performed at a time. Before sending the stop request to Deployment Center, the backend can check again the existence of the deployment cache in Redis to confirm the challenge is active. This mechanism helps limit duplicate stop operations or late requests continuing to affect the already-stopped deployment. In addition, instead of updating STOPPED status with short existence time when receiving Deleted event from Kubernetes, another approach is to completely delete the deployment cache entry in Redis. This method helps avoid the listener overwriting previous statuses and reduces the possibility of deviation between cache status and the actual status of resources on Kubernetes.
In general, the solutions proposed above help significantly reduce the possibility of race condition occurring in important operations of the system. Sensitive operations are protected by distributed locking mechanisms, deployment status is controlled more tightly through clear intermediate steps, and events from Kubernetes are processed in a parallel model but still ensure the necessary order. Thereby the system can achieve better data consistency, higher concurrent processing capability and ensure fairness in the competition process.
3.8.3.9. Upgrading DeploymentListener according to sharding + multi-worker model (SOL-15)
For the DeploymentListener component, an improvement direction is to process more efficiently when many Kubernetes events occur at the same time by classifying events according to each Pod UID and allocating them to multiple parallel processing workers. Events related to the same pod are sent to the same worker to ensure processing order within each shard, while other workers can process other pods simultaneously. This design helps reduce event backlog when infrastructure load increases, shortens latency in synchronizing RUNNING, STOPPED or DELETING status to Redis and database, while still preserving the sequentiality necessary for each pod.
3.8.4. Operational Efficiency & UX
3.8.4.1. Improving user experience on Monitoring page and Pod Log
a, Improving Monitoring and Pod Log filter set (SOL-16.1)
To solve the limitation in observability on Monitoring and log page, the system needs to add flexible filters and quick operations for active challenge instances. Expanding displayed data helps Admin and Jury recognize status, challenge type and related subjects faster when the system has many simultaneous instances.
This solution aims to reduce dependence on manual operations, while shortening search and incident handling time during competition operation.
b, Adding auto-refresh for Pod Log (SOL-16.2)
For the pod log viewing page, the system needs to implement a real-time update mechanism or at least a quick refresh function without having to reload the entire page. When logs are continuously synchronized, Admin and Jury can monitor the progress of the pod during deployment or debugging without interruption.
Supporting auto-refresh log helps enhance continuous event monitoring capability and improves operation experience in contests with many challenge instances running simultaneously.
c, Building mechanism to track request logs from challenge instance (SOL-16.3)
To solve the limitation when the system does not provide logs of requests that contestants send to challenge instances, the backend needs to be expanded to record important requests right at the business processing layer instead of depending on the client. This approach helps logs accurately reflect real user behavior and reduces the risk of spoofing or missing data.
Besides storing logs per request, the system needs to add a request log lookup interface for Admin and Jury with filters by team, user, challenge, request status and time period. When request logs are stored centrally and can be queried quickly, organizers will easily detect abnormal behavior, support incident investigation and increase transparency in the competition operation process.
3.8.4.2. Upgrading analysis capability on Dashboard (SOL-17)
The current Dashboard mainly provides overview information, does not support in-depth analysis metrics to serve challenge quality evaluation and player behavior. To solve this limitation, the system needs to add analysis metrics such as solve rate of each challenge, average solve time, number of incorrect submissions, number of hint usages and point distribution over time. In addition, the dashboard should also provide statistics on the most solved challenges, the least solved and number of solves by category. Adding these metrics helps the Dashboard become an effective data analysis tool, supporting organizers in evaluating exam difficulty and making appropriate adjustments for future competitions.
3.8.4.3. Building Reward Query function to serve awards (SOL-18)
To overcome the problem of having to perform manual operations to query data to determine award categories, the system needs to build a Reward Query module allowing Admin to query and aggregate data according to multiple criteria such as Top N teams, minimum points, first blood, category or time period. At the same time, the system should support exporting data to Excel or CSV. This function helps speed up result aggregation, reduce errors due to manual operations and ensure transparency when announcing awards.
3.8.4.4. Enhancing User and Team management capability (SOL-19)
To improve user and team management capability, the system needs to expand information in the User table by adding fields such as team name, role, verified status, hidden, or banned, and support corresponding filters. For Team, the system needs to display additional information about captain, number of members and allow filtering by status or country. These improvements help Admin easily track and manage participant data, especially in large-scale competitions.
3.8.4.5. Completing Submission management function (SOL-20)
The current Submission management function still lacks necessary data filtering tools and has some errors in the data export process. To solve this problem, the system needs to add filters by team, user and time in the Submission screen. At the same time, the export error needs to be fixed to ensure data is exported accurately according to correct or incorrect status. In addition, the system should also support the score reset function for dynamic challenges and allow Admin to adjust submission status in special cases. These improvements help the submission processing process become more flexible and ensure accuracy when operating competitions.
3.8.4.6. Building Instance History and long-term log storage mechanism (SOL-21)
Currently the system does not have a mechanism allowing review of the entire lifecycle history of challenge instances, causing difficulty when needing to trace or report after the competition. To solve this problem, the system needs to build an Instance History module for Admin. This module stores essential information such as creation time, instance stop time, corresponding user and team. Data is stored persistently in the database and supports search, filtering by multiple criteria as well as exporting data to CSV file. Adding this function helps increase event tracing capability, supports reporting and post-competition analysis.
3.8.4.7. Implementing system-wide Audit Log mechanism (SOL-22)
The current system does not have a mechanism to fully record administration operations, making tracing difficult when incidents or disputes occur. To solve this problem, an Audit Log mechanism needs to be implemented to record important actions of Admin, Jury and Challenge Writer such as editing challenges, changing configuration, handling submissions or updating user and team information. Log data needs to be designed in read-only mode to ensure it cannot be edited or deleted. This mechanism helps increase tracing capability, supports internal checking and ensures transparency in the CTF system operation process.
3.8.4.8. Implementing mechanism to view Action Log for administrators (SOL-23)
Besides recording logs, the system also needs to provide an intuitive interface so that administrators can look up and analyze activities that have occurred. To meet this need, an Action Log screen needs to be built in the Admin Interface allowing filtering by contest, user, team, action type, challenge and time period. The system also needs to support search, pagination and data export for reporting. In addition, the permission mechanism needs to be designed clearly to ensure each role can only access the appropriate log scope. This function helps enhance system monitoring capability, support cheating tracing and increase transparency in the competition organization process.
3.8.4.9. Improving Import/Export function (SOL-24)
The current import/export function still has some errors and does not provide detailed feedback information after processing batch data. To overcome this problem, the system needs to complete the import/export mechanism to ensure data is processed stably with CSV files or configuration templates. At the same time, it needs to add import result reports, including number of successful records, failures and skipped cases (for example: username already exists). These improvements help Admin easily control the data entry process, reduce errors and increase reliability when operating with large numbers of records.
3.8.4.10. Improving bracket division function and scoreboard data display (SOL-25)
To overcome the current limitations of the bracket function, the system needs to add some improvements in both Contestant Portal and Admin Interface.
On the Contestant Portal, the Scoreboard page needs to support filtering by bracket, allowing contestants to choose to view the ranking table of the entire competition or only within the scope of their bracket. This feature helps contestants easily track their position in the corresponding classification group.
On Admin Interface, the system needs to complete the bracket management function, allowing administrators to assign users or teams to each bracket and view the member list in each group. At the same time, the Visibility configuration section needs to add options to allow or restrict displaying scoreboard between brackets.
These improvements help increase flexibility when organizing competitions with many groups of participants, while improving the ranking table tracking experience for contestants.
3.8.4.11. Building automated CI/CD process for system deployment (SOL-26)
To overcome the weakness of the manual deployment process, a feasible solution is for the system to be supplemented with an automated CI/CD pipeline based on GitHub Actions, triggered when changes are pushed to the main branch. The pipeline performs build and deployment of services to the cluster automatically, while only rebuilding services affected by source code changes to optimize processing time.
The deployment process is controlled through rollout status checking steps to ensure updates are applied successfully before completing the pipeline. In addition, concurrency management mechanism is also integrated to avoid multiple pipelines deploying to the production environment at the same time causing conflicts. Thanks to this mechanism, the deployment process that previously required many manual operations is simplified to one git push operation, helping to reduce human errors, ensure the production environment is always synchronized with the latest source code and allow faster release of updates or security patches.
3.8.4.12. Challenge Management Improvements
a, Upgrading View Challenges and Search Challenges (SOL-27)
To solve the limitation in observability and data retrieval of challenges, the system needs to be improved towards increasing transparency and information filtering capability. Expanding displayed information and supporting flexible filtering mechanisms helps users quickly grasp the status and characteristics of each challenge in the system.
This solution aims to reduce dependence on manual operations, while improving administration efficiency when the number of challenges increases. When search and classification capability is optimized, administrators can make decisions faster and minimize errors in the contest operation process.
b, Adding full deployment configuration for challenges (SOL-28)
An important weakness of the current system is the limited ability to control deployment configuration, especially related to resources and isolation level. Therefore, a tighter configuration management approach needs to be applied to ensure each challenge is deployed in a controlled environment.
Adding resource configuration parameters and validity checking mechanism before deployment helps minimize the risk of system overload and configuration errors. At the same time, enhancing this control capability also contributes to improving the stability of the entire infrastructure, especially in the context of many challenges being deployed simultaneously.
c, Full support for dynamic challenges (SOL-29)
To support challenges with point reduction mechanism according to the number of correct submissions, the system needs to add dynamic challenge type with separate configuration fields such as current value, initial value, decay function, decay value and minimum value. The administration interface needs to allow Challenge Writers to choose the appropriate point reduction function type, for example Linear or Logarithmic, and clearly display the current point value for easy tracking during the competition.
At the business processing layer, the backend needs to recalculate the challenge points based on the number of teams or players who have solved correctly and update this value consistently after each valid submission. This design helps the system correctly reflect the competitive behavior of the contest, increase flexibility for question setters and better suit modern CTF models.
d, Building challenge version management mechanism (SOL-30)
To solve the problem of challenge changes being overwritten directly, the system needs to save each challenge edit as a separate version. Each version should include information about creation time, Docker configuration, flag, resource settings and description content at that time. The Version History interface needs to support viewing the version list in chronological order, and also allow viewing details of each version to compare configurations.
Storing version history helps Challenge Writers and Admins easily trace changes, quickly detect which update caused build/deploy errors, and maintain challenge quality control over time. This is an important foundation to reduce risks when operating long-running contests.
e, Establishing safe challenge version rollback process (SOL-31)
In real operation environment, the ability to quickly restore to stable status is an important factor. Therefore, the system needs to support a controlled rollback mechanism, allowing return to previous versions in a consistent way.
This solution helps significantly reduce recovery time when challenges have built or deploy errors, while avoiding manual editing that is easy to cause errors. When rollback is attached to version history and automatic redeployment process, the system can return to stable status quickly and under control.
f, Adding Shared Instance challenge type (SOL-32)
To address this limitation, the system introduces a “Shared Instance” option for challenges. When enabled, a single shared environment is deployed and accessed by all teams. Changes are applied at both the data and backend layers to support this mode and ensure a consistent state across all teams. The solution remains fully backward compatible: existing challenges behave as before, while only those with “Shared Instance” enabled use the new model.
3.8.4.13. Transitioning service and challenge image registry (SOL-33)
To address the dependency on Docker Hub, the system should use Harbor as the unified self-hosted image registry for all F-CTF core services as well as challenge images. The CI/CD build pipeline will push all system component images (Contestant Portal, Admin MVC, Backend services, etc.) and challenge artifacts directly to Harbor, and deployment workflows will pull images exclusively from Harbor, keeping the full image supply chain under organizational control. Harbor provides project-level access control, TLS, audit logs, vulnerability scanning, and image retention policies, which makes it highly suitable for a competition platform that manages both sensitive challenge images and critical system services. Moving to Harbor removes the 20 GB free private-repository limit of Docker Hub, centralizes image management, and eliminates the operational risk of relying on an external third-party registry for production deployments and platform updates.
3.8.5. Solution Group for Architecture and Security (SOL-1)
Based on the analyzed vulnerabilities and risks, the remediation process will focus on re-establishing a secure architecture following the principles of least privilege and defense-in-depth across all system layers. The core objective is to isolate components, minimize the blast radius in the event of an incident, and eliminate redundant privileges that are unnecessary for business operations.
At the network layer, the system must immediately implement NetworkPolicies with a default-deny principle for both ingress and egress traffic. Instead of the current open network model, internal communication flows between pods will only be permitted when explicitly declared based on actual needs. Simultaneously, to counter the risk of data theft through internal packet sniffing, all communication traffic between services must be encrypted through the deployment of mTLS, ensuring the confidentiality of sensitive information such as tokens and challenge flags.
For the MariaDB database, restructuring authorization is an extremely urgent task. Administrators must immediately disable remote access capabilities for the superuser account, only allowing this account to connect from the local environment. The current shared account with full privileges must be removed and replaced with independent database accounts for each separate service. Each of these accounts will be strictly configured to limit access rights, only allowing query, insert, or update operations on the exact data tables that the service requires to process its business logic, absolutely preventing cross-data interference.
The security hardening process for Redis will begin by enabling the Access Control List (ACL) mechanism and completely disabling the uncontrolled default user. The system will create separate Redis users for each component, such as the admin interface, gateway, or deployment services. These accounts will be strictly limited to operating only on data key prefixes within their scope and will only be allowed to use a minimized command set. Specifically, destructive or system-monitoring commands such as configuration changes, full data flushes, server shutdowns, or traffic monitoring must be completely blocked or renamed to prevent the risk of abuse.
Regarding shared storage, the PersistentVolumes connected to NFS must be immediately updated with secure mount options (such as noexec) to prohibit the execution of any binary files from this storage space. Data boundary fragmentation will be enforced through directory-level access control lists, ensuring each service or CI/CD workflow only has read and write permissions on its exact designated directory. The NFS server configuration also needs to be adjusted to prevent containers running with the highest administrative privileges from modifying the file ownership of other services on the shared partition.
Finally, for the orchestration and monitoring infrastructure, all connections to the Argo Workflows server must be transitioned to the HTTPS encrypted protocol to protect authentication tokens. The orchestration system must be supplemented with restriction rules so that only approved workflow templates are capable of execution. Container groups without the need to communicate with the cluster management system will have their automatic service account token mounting feature disabled. Concurrently, the Grafana monitoring platform will be configured using an infrastructure-as-code approach to lock the editing functionality of default dashboards, ensuring the integrity of observability data under any attack scenario.
